WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.200
[Amit Varma]: We like to think that India is a free country and that we are free thinkers, but the truth

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:16.600
[Amit Varma]: is that we are still colonized. We think about the world and about our society through frames

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:21.760
[Amit Varma]: that have been constructed by others. As an illustration of this, ask yourself what comes

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:26.680
[Amit Varma]: to mind when you think of the word, the wife. Is the image that comes to mind that of a

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:31.240
[Amit Varma]: fallen sex worker, someone worthy only of contempt or pity? Or do you get the image

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:36.240
[Amit Varma]: of a bewitching courtesan out of Bollywood, dressed in an intricately embroidered anarkali,

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: glowing with the jewelry she is wearing under the light of a crystal chandelier, Rekha or

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:45.720
[Amit Varma]: Meena Kumari at their most beautiful? Both these images are false. But these common impressions

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:52.240
[Amit Varma]: of the wives reveal a lot about our own prejudices. If only we cared to examine them closely and

00:00:52.240 --> 00:01:01.400
[Unknown]: examine where they came from. Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:07.520
[Unknown]: economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Sabha Dewan, filmmaker and author

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:19.960
[Amit Varma]: who has made a series of riveting documentaries, including the 2009 film, The Other Song that

00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:24.840
[Amit Varma]: journeys through Varanasi, Lucknow and Muzaffarpur, looking at the lives and histories of the

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:29.200
[Amit Varma]: wives. She had immersed herself so deeply in the subject that when she was done with

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:34.200
[Amit Varma]: the film, she wrote a book called Tawaif Nama, which is filled with some incredible stories

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:41.280
[Amit Varma]: as also social insights that come out of history and sit uneasily in our present times. I'm

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:45.520
[Amit Varma]: delighted that Sabha has agreed to join me on the show today. But before we begin our

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:50.560
[Amit Varma]: conversation, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:54.120
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:59.160
[Amit Varma]: show alive. The Scene and the Unseen has been a labor of love for me. I've enjoyed putting

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:04.600
[Amit Varma]: together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe and hopefully yours

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:09.480
[Amit Varma]: as well. But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off

00:02:09.480 --> 00:02:14.080
[Amit Varma]: the show. Although The Scene and the Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:19.040
[Amit Varma]: woken up to the insane engagement level of podcasts. I do many, many hours of deep research

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:25.400
[Amit Varma]: for each episode, besides all the logistics of producing the show myself, scheduling guests,

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:30.840
[Amit Varma]: booking studios, paying technicians, the travel and so on. So well, I'm trying a new way of

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:36.440
[Amit Varma]: keeping this thing going. And that involves you. My proposition for you is this. For every

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:41.600
[Amit Varma]: episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:46.560
[Amit Varma]: lunch, whatever you feel it's worth. You can do this by heading over to sceneunseen.in

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:52.840
[Amit Varma]: slash support and contributing an amount of your choice. This is not a subscription. The

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:59.640
[Amit Varma]: Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at sceneunseen.in.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:06.040
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help keep the scene going. sceneunseen.in slash

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:07.040
[Amit Varma]: support.

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Saba, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. Thank you. Thank you for having me on the

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:18.680
[Amit Varma]: show. Before we sort of start talking about Tawaif Nama and you know, everything that's

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:22.960
[Amit Varma]: in the book, tell me a little bit about you know, your own personal journey. How did you

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:28.160
[Amit Varma]: become a filmmaker? How did all this happen? How did I become a filmmaker? Oh, Lord, that

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:33.920
[Guest]: was years back. Well, actually, it started off initially, as a kind of a rebellion. Both

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:41.440
[Guest]: my parents were journalists, and it was expected that I'd become a journalist. And so of course,

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:46.600
[Guest]: I didn't want to become a journalist. So the next best thing I could think of was to be

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:54.800
[Guest]: a filmmaker. But jokes apart, actually, I was interested in films. And I then joined

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:59.960
[Guest]: the Mass Communication Research Center, Jamia. Although at that time, I wasn't very clear,

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:06.400
[Guest]: even at that age, about the difference between documentaries or fiction. So I joined innocently

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:12.000
[Guest]: enough thinking cinema karenge, filme banayenge. And then hey, presto, found myself in this

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:21.240
[Guest]: place where, you know, the entire focus was on the documentary genre. And that opened

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:28.120
[Guest]: a completely wide new world for me. I mean, it was and the beauty of the documentary,

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:35.680
[Guest]: you know, the beauty of reality, and how slippery a creature reality is, and how difficult it

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:41.640
[Guest]: is to define reality, your reality might not be my reality. So I mean, it throws up all

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:47.840
[Guest]: these questions. And that's, that's pretty much how I entered the field.

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:53.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, as a kid in the 1980s, I remember that to me when I thought of films and popular

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.840
[Amit Varma]: culture, documentaries were like the most boring thing out there. They were that films

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.960
[Amit Varma]: revision stuff that you saw once a week on Doordarshan or whatever, and it was boring

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:05.680
[Amit Varma]: as hell. And obviously, documentaries are a lot more than that. So you know, when did

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:10.360
[Amit Varma]: you first get that spark of discovery that wait a minute, this is not some boring thing

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:14.240
[Amit Varma]: about something, you know, where somebody is droning on and on and stuff you're not

00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:17.080
[Amit Varma]: interested about, you can create magic out of this.

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:21.520
[Guest]: At Mass Communication Research Center, I pretty much thought the same. You know, I was quite

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:27.040
[Guest]: horrified when I realized that I was at a place where they specialized in documentaries.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:33.160
[Guest]: So, you know, I had these visions of like being condemned to making these awful films

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:41.520
[Guest]: division documentaries. But we think I think we had some wonderful teachers at that point,

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:49.080
[Guest]: and also exposure to world cinema. And we saw documentaries, you know, which was certainly

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:56.640
[Guest]: not like the films division propaganda that we had grown up associating documentaries

00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:04.680
[Guest]: with. And also, the early 80s was a very exciting time for the Indian documentary because the

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: Indian documentary, independent documentary was coming into its own, you know, away from

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.200
[Guest]: state funding. And that was the time when we were students and we were discovering documentary.

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:23.080
[Guest]: So, we were exposed to the work of people like Meera Nair, and Deepal Sanraj, and Navrose,

00:06:23.080 --> 00:06:27.200
[Guest]: Anand Patwardhan. And we were very lucky, we're quite blessed to have them actually

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:34.120
[Guest]: come and show their films to us and talk to us. And so yeah, and, you know, even in terms

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:40.360
[Guest]: of world cinema and documentaries, international documentaries, I think there was a certain

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:48.920
[Guest]: kind of an exposure that we got at Jamia, which then, you know, opened us to the possibilities

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:56.880
[Guest]: of documentaries being an extremely creative medium. So, you know, and extremely exciting.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:02.320
[Guest]: I mean, documentary, or if that's the matter with any art, is what you make it to be.

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And that was also an exciting time for cinema in the sense Shyam Banegar, Govind Yalini,

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:12.160
[Amit Varma]: the whole, all of that was also happening. Yes. So, did you also look at that and, you

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.200
[Amit Varma]: know, think that, okay, maybe I want to make the shift someday and make feature films or

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:20.960
[Amit Varma]: were you already so excited by what documentaries could do that you were just happy where you

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:21.960
[Guest]: were?

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:27.160
[Guest]: I was, we were also exposed to, you know, world cinema in terms of fiction. So, it was

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:35.160
[Guest]: an exciting time, both for fiction and nonfiction. And yes, I mean, I think in the initial years,

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:42.560
[Guest]: there was always this feeling that someday I'll make a fiction, you know, feature film.

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:49.480
[Guest]: But you know, in the thing is that somehow, while working on the documentary, and over

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:58.120
[Guest]: the period of time, documentary stopped becoming a poor cousin to the feature film, at least

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:05.880
[Guest]: for me, as a filmmaker, because it offers just so many exciting possibilities. And it,

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:09.960
[Guest]: it's also very challenging as a medium, because I mean, there is, of course, that much that

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:14.240
[Guest]: you have planned. But with a documentary, there's just so much that you possibly cannot

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:22.640
[Guest]: plan, and which comes in and if you're receptive to it, it can bring magic to what you're doing.

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:31.000
[Guest]: So I think that initial stage, yes, it was always like, or documentary is like a stepping

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.040
[Guest]: stone to feature films, but that was in the initial stage, then you pretty much realise

00:08:36.040 --> 00:08:41.600
[Guest]: that documentary actually is a huge challenge in itself. And in many ways, I think more

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:45.160
[Guest]: challenging, because there's just so much that's not in your control.

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:49.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I guess with a feature film, you've constructed a narrative and that's it, you

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.200
[Amit Varma]: follow the script, but with the documentary, you're sort of...

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:56.320
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I'm sure with feature films, it's extremely challenging. And it's not only

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:02.760
[Guest]: a certain senior linear progression. That's not, you know, what I meant. But I mean, that

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:08.600
[Guest]: in a documentary, you could say, I'm going to do this, you could land up in a place,

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:13.920
[Guest]: and the character that you had kind of spent time with, etc, etc. And, you know, thought

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:18.600
[Guest]: she was all ready to shoot with you. And suddenly something's happened. You know, there's some

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:24.840
[Guest]: death in the family or something, some emergency, and she's gone. And so pretty much you are

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:29.040
[Guest]: there, but your character is gone. And so what are you going to do? Either you cancel

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:34.280
[Guest]: your shoot, or you think of something else to do. I think those are the ways I think

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:40.200
[Guest]: as a documentary filmmaker, you've got to be really, really very resourceful. And, you

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:45.360
[Guest]: know, trying to work out things at the spot.

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:49.080
[Amit Varma]: And did you fall into that trap early on that, you know, you go there with a fixed sort of

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:53.600
[Amit Varma]: notion in mind, a fixed narrative in mind, but then you have to adapt? Or were you aware

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:56.240
[Amit Varma]: from the start that you just have to leave yourself open?

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:03.800
[Guest]: No, I think mercifully, you know, I, I think it was also the kind of training we had at

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:09.720
[Guest]: Jamia. I mean, we were lucky because, you know, we had Professor James Beveridge is

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:17.960
[Guest]: one of the stalwarts of the documentary, Canadian documentary. And it's he who he and his wife,

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:24.120
[Guest]: Margaret, who was an ace editor, who helped set up the film school at Jamia. We were lucky

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:31.360
[Guest]: to have him as our teacher. So the emphasis was actually on cinema verity of, of, you

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:40.400
[Guest]: know, shooting as unfolding as things happen. So you don't construct. And you don't feed

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:46.160
[Guest]: people lines. But that's the simpler aspect of it. I think what is more problematic, and

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:53.200
[Guest]: I think a lot of filmmakers tend to fall into that trap. And I think a lot of times that

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:59.240
[Guest]: comes a out of ignorance of not knowing better, and be out of a certain arrogance, which is

00:10:59.240 --> 00:11:04.280
[Guest]: that you presume someone's reality, that you understand someone's reality. And you presume

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:09.200
[Guest]: where they're coming from. And you presume that they're going to say this, or they ought

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:15.840
[Guest]: to say this, and this ought to be their understanding. And a lot of people fall into that trap, even

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:21.040
[Guest]: in terms of very political filmmaking, you know, there's the subaltern, the subaltern

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:26.080
[Guest]: has to be in the vanguard of the revolution, the subaltern may not be on the vanguard of

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:35.440
[Guest]: the revolution, you know. And so, so, I think I did start off with certain notions, because

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:42.160
[Guest]: how can not someone not be like that, you know, you those presumptions, but I think

00:11:42.160 --> 00:11:53.200
[Guest]: as you grow older, and hopefully a bit wiser, and also, you get enough knocks in life, to

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:59.320
[Guest]: get some humility dinked into you, to realize that you don't have the answer. And it's good.

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:04.120
[Guest]: It's good, you don't have all the answers. Because that's the only way that you can relate

00:12:04.120 --> 00:12:12.720
[Guest]: to people as human beings to human beings, not as like filmmaker here, and subject there.

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:21.120
[Guest]: And it's only then when you can have the two people, you are talking to people as people,

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:28.760
[Guest]: without any preconceived expectations. That makes for a real conversation, actually a

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:33.920
[Guest]: meaningful conversation. I think that took me time. And that was the biggest learning

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:34.920
[Amit Varma]: process.

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:37.800
[Amit Varma]: And what kind of subjects were you drawn to?

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:44.840
[Guest]: You know, a lot of my work has been with women, for the very simple reason that I am a woman.

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:52.280
[Guest]: And I think I understand women better. Women interest me, women's lives interest me. That's

00:12:52.280 --> 00:13:00.440
[Guest]: I think the most important thing. And having been part of the feminist movement and, you

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:07.520
[Guest]: know, believing in a certain kind of a politics. Yes, I'm drawn to the kind of challenges that

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:15.840
[Guest]: women face. So yeah, my protagonists have mostly been women. But the subject, the subjects

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:21.280
[Guest]: could be any, you know, a lot of my work has been political, and working in the realm of

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:31.200
[Guest]: culture. So it's a pretty diverse portfolio in that sense. You know, that is a work with,

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:38.240
[Guest]: you know, survivors of abusive marriages. But then I've also worked with girls and young

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:44.480
[Guest]: women going to the mountains for the first time, and just a trek film, which is a fun

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:50.640
[Guest]: film. And then of course, I've worked with this trilogy that I did, which is the other

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:58.960
[Guest]: song is part of that trilogy, which is on, you know, stigmatized female performers. So

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:06.720
[Guest]: I'm kind of moved. And I've also worked, done a film on the women of my own family. It's

00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:13.120
[Guest]: called Sita's family, looking at middle class women and looking at the kind of issues that

00:14:13.120 --> 00:14:19.520
[Guest]: they face. I mean, women who, you know, made the choice of, you know, working outside the

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:24.720
[Guest]: house, but then what are the kind of expectations that society has of them, but more importantly,

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:29.520
[Guest]: which they impose on themselves, the kind of, you know, expectations that they've internalized

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:33.680
[Amit Varma]: about being good women. So, yeah.

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:37.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, like, one of the things that has struck me over the last few years reading

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:43.840
[Amit Varma]: history and doing a lot of episodes with historians, is that we take the male gaze on history for

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:47.840
[Amit Varma]: granted. Most of history, of course, is told from a male gaze. And therefore, there is

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:53.480
[Amit Varma]: a lot that is invisible or unseen, as it were, to that gaze. And it struck me while reading

00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:59.320
[Amit Varma]: your book that so much of the book also sort of deals with that about making that unseen

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:05.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of visible. And what I also found sort of fascinating was, you know, one is, of course,

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:09.160
[Amit Varma]: the cliched ways of looking at the virus, which I sort of referred to in the introduction,

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:16.680
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, what I grew up with, at least. So, you know, so this is sort of pretty

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:20.440
[Amit Varma]: much what you thought, and then you peel back the layers. And, you know, another thing that

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:24.760
[Amit Varma]: I have sort of discovered in recent episodes with historians is how so much of what we

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:30.480
[Amit Varma]: think of our own society and culture is constructed by the British when they came here, because

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:35.200
[Amit Varma]: they were obviously looking for simplistic narratives to explain the world to themselves,

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:39.040
[Amit Varma]: so they could neatly categorize everything. You in your book, of course, referred to Francis

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:43.400
[Amit Varma]: Buchanan, but this was pretty much the attitude of the British from the late 18th century

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:47.960
[Amit Varma]: onwards that they're trying to figure it out. They have access to only the elites who are,

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:53.000
[Amit Varma]: of course, upper caste Brahmins, so they get that sort of a version of history and then

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:59.840
[Amit Varma]: that gets ossified. And the rich, thriving sort of culture of the wives, you know, then

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:03.960
[Amit Varma]: they shine this moralistic light on it and everything just changes. Tell me a little

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:05.960
[Guest]: bit about this process.

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:15.360
[Guest]: See, we need to understand a few things. The thing is not that, you know, I think what

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:20.200
[Guest]: the book doesn't deal with it in that greater detail, although I do mention it, and which

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:27.040
[Guest]: is that the wives, it's not as if before the India was colonized or before the British

00:16:27.040 --> 00:16:34.120
[Guest]: came, the wives occupied a highly respectable position in society, which is the book. The

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:41.680
[Guest]: book keeps actually, you know, reiterating that they enjoyed high prestige, which is

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:46.480
[Guest]: not the same as being respectable, you know, because they were attached to the nobility

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:54.460
[Guest]: and individual men of the elite and the court. So they had access to power, they had access

00:16:54.460 --> 00:17:01.660
[Guest]: to wealth. And they were, of course, very sought after performers, musicians and dancers,

00:17:01.660 --> 00:17:09.800
[Guest]: in many cases also poets and writers and patrons of actually artists. They occupied a very

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:16.480
[Guest]: ambiguous space between, you know, repute and disrepute, which is because of the certain

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:24.720
[Guest]: stigma of being out of purdah. And, you know, out in the gaze of available, actually to

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:32.240
[Guest]: all technically, although they were not. But yes, I mean, you know, it's out in the gaze

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:39.360
[Guest]: of men. And yet they had a certain designated space within society. They were not certainly

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: not looked down upon. In fact, people, you know, there was this much sought after too.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.240
[Guest]: And what was also very interesting, and if while I was researching was, it's not just

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:57.760
[Guest]: the men that they've had relationships with, they actually would be invited at points of

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:05.440
[Guest]: time by the women in the zanana, not very often, but they did. And so to perform on

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:13.920
[Guest]: certain special occasions, etc., which I think is an important point, because the ways in

00:18:13.920 --> 00:18:20.720
[Guest]: which patriarchy insulates, you know, women of disrepute from what are the pure women.

00:18:20.720 --> 00:18:25.440
[Guest]: With tawafs that was not exactly happening. So I mean, not all tawafs, but tawafs of the

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:31.720
[Guest]: highest repute, for instance, did have some access to the zananas of the aristocracy,

00:18:31.720 --> 00:18:38.120
[Guest]: because we have mention of that, even in the novel Umrao Jaanada, which actually is, you

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:46.040
[Guest]: know, is hailed for its very, very authentic portrayal of 19th century Lucknow, makes mention

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:54.120
[Guest]: of that. I think what happens with the coming on of the British is as you know, as you have

00:18:54.120 --> 00:18:59.520
[Guest]: mentioned very rightly, it's not just the tawafs. I mean, there was pretty much it happened

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:07.840
[Guest]: with everything where here is, you know, an alien government, a colonial government, trying

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:15.920
[Guest]: to understand in the simplest possible terms, a subject people and a subject people, which,

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:24.280
[Guest]: you know, I mean, the most bewildering variety possible and heterogeneity amongst them. So

00:19:24.280 --> 00:19:33.200
[Guest]: it's not Europe, they chose to colonize India, which is an entire subcontinent in itself.

00:19:33.200 --> 00:19:39.600
[Guest]: And you know, they had confronted with this kind of a heterogeneity. So one of the ways

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:46.640
[Guest]: in which one and you know, colonizers deal with heterogeneity is to actually somewhere

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:54.440
[Guest]: smoothen out the differences and to, you know, make uniform or at least impose a certain

00:19:54.440 --> 00:20:00.640
[Guest]: uniformity of understanding. So yeah, you they had, you know, you have these volley

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:06.000
[Guest]: of ethnographers, self-styled ethnographers, they're not ethnographers, ethnographers,

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:10.320
[Guest]: but travellers who could be missionaries, who could be administrators, who could be

00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:15.360
[Guest]: colonial traders, you know, I mean, it's a variety of people who are travelling in India

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:21.560
[Guest]: and making copious notes about all manner of, you know, subjects pertaining to the so-called

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:30.080
[Guest]: native life. But it is not only actually an exercise in naivety, or even in terms of,

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:37.120
[Guest]: you know, trying to understand an alien people. It is also informed by the imperatives of

00:20:37.120 --> 00:20:43.600
[Guest]: colonization itself. So it's not entirely an innocent exercise. And there is a certain

00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:49.720
[Guest]: imperative, there's an imperative of, you know, divide and rule. And much as it sounds

00:20:49.720 --> 00:20:56.440
[Guest]: a cliche now, the fact is that there is ways in which there is a constant refrain about

00:20:56.440 --> 00:21:01.440
[Guest]: Hindus and Muslims. Whereas the interesting thing is that actually in the early ethnographic

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:07.480
[Guest]: records, there are communities upon communities of people who return themselves as both Hindus

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:13.340
[Guest]: and Muslims, much to the chagrin of, you know, the colonial ethnographers, because how can

00:21:13.340 --> 00:21:14.880
[Guest]: you be both Hindu and Muslim?

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:19.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact, even the term Hindu encompasses so much less than what it does today, it's practically

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:20.680
[Guest]: reconstructed.

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:25.680
[Guest]: It's a 19th century term, actually. And people not returning themselves as Hindus, people

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:32.480
[Guest]: are returning themselves as Bhumiyar or this or that, you know, it's caste based. So this

00:21:32.480 --> 00:21:38.960
[Guest]: ways in which there is a certain homogenizing of putting them under a certain labeling people,

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:45.320
[Guest]: that process takes place with the coming of the British process gets consolidated, solidified

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:52.000
[Guest]: with that entire process of census, you know, which from, I think, 1891 or something when

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:57.100
[Guest]: first census records start getting collected.

00:21:57.100 --> 00:22:04.320
[Guest]: But there's also a process in which especially after 1857, where there are ways in which

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:11.840
[Guest]: there is a certain stereotypes being created, and quite consciously being created and projected.

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:17.680
[Guest]: Among those stereotypes, you know, are the stereotypes of the decadent, depraved, you

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:26.400
[Guest]: know, less vicious, Indian male, especially Indian princes, and who are more usually Muslim

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:34.560
[Guest]: Nawabs, but could be actually also Hindus. Because this is the ruling class, the native

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:41.520
[Guest]: ruling class that stood up against colonial might in 1857. So there's ways in which they

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:48.280
[Guest]: are being maligned, and the kind of lifestyle associated with them then is portrayed as

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:49.280
[Guest]: decadent.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:57.920
[Guest]: Now, here, of course, I think what also happens is that evangelism and Victorian morality

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:03.920
[Guest]: also come into play, because a figure of a Tawaf makes no sense. She can only be a prostitute.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:08.720
[Guest]: In fact, that treatment is given not just to Tawafs, but even the Afdasis. So any female

00:23:08.720 --> 00:23:15.840
[Guest]: sexuality that exists outside of marriage has to be prostitute. So in fact, that is

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:21.760
[Guest]: an entire spectrum that gets labelled as prostitute, not just the Tawafs.

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:26.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, what also sort of strikes me as interesting is that there are almost like

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:32.240
[Amit Varma]: two forms of patriarchy playing out here. One, of course, is that the very existence

00:23:32.240 --> 00:23:37.200
[Amit Varma]: of Tawafs, as almost a separate class and a separate community of people, points to

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:41.760
[Amit Varma]: the fact that the rest of the women, the women who are married, who are part of households,

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:46.800
[Amit Varma]: are supposed to keep their sexuality repressed. So that's a separate class. And therefore,

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:51.040
[Amit Varma]: because you want singing, dancing women who are expressing themselves freely, it's almost

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:57.480
[Amit Varma]: as if there is a necessity for a community of Tawafs, who then kind of looked at differently,

00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:01.880
[Amit Varma]: but without necessarily the moral stigma, which then the British bring to it and the

00:24:01.880 --> 00:24:06.160
[Amit Varma]: British come with this moral stigma at this sort of sexual expression, blah, blah, blah,

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:10.280
[Amit Varma]: they give a moral colour to it. And you know, even the sort of like, every time I hear of

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:15.880
[Amit Varma]: Tawafs being painted as sex workers and prostitutes, and the first thing I think that it strikes

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:19.920
[Amit Varma]: me we have to fight is what is wrong with sex workers and prostitutes to begin with?

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:24.960
[Amit Varma]: Why should you know that be a slur, but given that it is and is one of the things that we've

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:30.920
[Amit Varma]: normalised and is there, regardless, it's a huge step down. The other question I wanted

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:37.280
[Amit Varma]: to ask was, how empowered are the Tawafs in the sense that in contrast to the other women

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:42.600
[Amit Varma]: in society, they appear to have more autonomy, like sure, they function within that patriarchal

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:47.520
[Amit Varma]: setup, and they have to cater to the wishes of men. And that's what they are trained for.

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:51.840
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, within that setup, they can shape their destiny far more, they are

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:56.600
[Amit Varma]: the heads of their communities. As you pointed out, for example, they even get a major share

00:24:56.600 --> 00:25:02.320
[Amit Varma]: of the revenue share, like, you know, if there are 16 Annas, nine goes to the Tawaf and whatever,

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:07.920
[Amit Varma]: and they have a very sort of respected place within that community. So, you know, looking

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:12.320
[Amit Varma]: back as a feminist, and obviously, these are not people who are feminists per se, they

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:17.320
[Amit Varma]: are making the best of what they can within that system. What's your sense of these different

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:21.040
[Amit Varma]: degrees of autonomy and how these women are trying to negotiate these spaces?

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:25.600
[Guest]: You know, I wouldn't, I refrained and even in the book, I refrained from using terms

00:25:25.600 --> 00:25:32.960
[Guest]: like empowered, because A, Tawafs don't exist as a community. We are talking about them

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:40.960
[Guest]: in the past tense, necessarily, because that community has been wiped out. And two, I think

00:25:40.960 --> 00:25:48.640
[Guest]: there are, you know, terms like being empowered, for instance, or liberated. We, these, you

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:56.400
[Guest]: know, the present context coming out of a certain politics in the present, I am very

00:25:56.400 --> 00:26:03.720
[Guest]: hesitant to use those parameters for in the past. Because, you know, I mean, you have

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:10.680
[Guest]: to see and understand reality within in the past context, in the historical context, within

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:17.720
[Guest]: those parameters of the given parameters of those times. Yes, definitely, relatively speaking,

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:22.840
[Guest]: and I will keep using the term relative, because it was relative. The fact is that the wives

00:26:22.840 --> 00:26:29.280
[Guest]: were not independent of patriarchy. They were very much an adjunct of patriarchy. The community

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:35.840
[Guest]: existed because of patriarchy, you know, patriarchy and in the sense of male entitlement, which

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:43.360
[Guest]: wanted actually their wives, but also wanted to have these, you know, fascinating, beautiful,

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:51.080
[Guest]: talented, witty, you know, mistresses. So I mean, so the fact is that definitely, male

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:57.600
[Guest]: entitlement was at the base of, you know, the existence of the wives or devdasis that

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:01.160
[Amit Varma]: goes without saying. So it's like the men are making these boxes to put women in and

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:06.720
[Guest]: this particular box has more space within it. But it never, you see, I think what happens

00:27:06.720 --> 00:27:13.800
[Guest]: though is that socially when and with human beings, it never quite works out as you expect

00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:17.880
[Guest]: it to. So for instance, even in terms of, you know, when you're saying that in terms

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:23.840
[Guest]: of women of the household being sexually repressed, that's our presumption living in the 21st

00:27:23.840 --> 00:27:30.600
[Guest]: century. You know, there's enough writing and glimpses that one gets of the Zanana,

00:27:30.600 --> 00:27:36.880
[Guest]: which seems to have been a pretty thriving sexual space, which, you know, which is something

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:41.520
[Guest]: that, but then one would have to understand it within the context of that space. If we

00:27:41.520 --> 00:27:48.160
[Guest]: try to start posing our understanding of what is active, being sexually active or sexually

00:27:48.160 --> 00:27:53.400
[Guest]: liberated, it doesn't work out that way. Similarly, with the Thawars. Yes, obviously, I mean,

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:58.520
[Guest]: they were there as adjunct and they were very much adjunct of patriarchy. Their entire existence

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:04.640
[Guest]: was dependent upon the patronage that they received from men. Without that, they're nothing.

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:10.040
[Guest]: But given all that, within that, the fact is that here's a community of women where

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:16.600
[Guest]: it is the women within the community who call the shots. You know, they are the ones, for

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:21.720
[Guest]: instance, who are the head of the households. They are the ones who are the karta of the

00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:28.960
[Guest]: house, you know, in terms of the Hindu undivided family. The Thawar head of the family, actually

00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:36.120
[Guest]: her position corresponded more or less to the eldest son of the Hindu undivided family.

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:41.360
[Guest]: They are the ones who, you know, depending, I mean, the laws of inheritance were different

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:47.800
[Guest]: for different castes and communities of Thawars. But in many communities, Thawar daughters

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:53.880
[Guest]: got a larger share, for instance, of the inheritance from their mothers and aunts, etc. than their

00:28:53.880 --> 00:28:57.840
[Guest]: brothers. In many other communities, at least the community I worked with, they got an equal

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:03.240
[Guest]: share. Sisters and brothers had an equal share. It varied from community to community. But

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:07.920
[Guest]: then they were much wealthier, ultimately, because they also held their own property.

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:14.720
[Guest]: They made their own property. These were self-made women. So they were also jodhrayans of the

00:29:14.720 --> 00:29:22.040
[Guest]: community at large. The community itself was not just made up of women. It was also made

00:29:22.040 --> 00:29:29.360
[Guest]: up of the accompanist musicians, the tabla players, the sarangi players, the majira players,

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:35.040
[Guest]: all of whom were men, who were teachers to Thawars, who were also their accompanists,

00:29:35.040 --> 00:29:40.280
[Guest]: and who were also dependent on Thawars for their livelihood. And in every town, you know,

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:45.280
[Guest]: you had these kota communities, and it was the Thawars, and they had their own system

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:50.120
[Guest]: of, you know, panchayat or council, which to regulate the affairs, internal affairs

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:56.880
[Guest]: of the community. And it was the Thawars who headed these panchayats, always. So, you know,

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:02.000
[Guest]: in terms of the household, it is they had definitely, it is they who called the shots

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:06.720
[Guest]: of how the house would be run, you know, the family would be run. And they had relatively

00:30:06.720 --> 00:30:13.760
[Guest]: greater autonomy, in terms of also choosing who to take on as a lover and who not to,

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:18.480
[Guest]: which now that depended, you know, if you came from, you're a poor Thawar, and you came

00:30:18.480 --> 00:30:24.400
[Guest]: from, you know, a poorer family, you might not have the luxury to exercise that choice,

00:30:24.400 --> 00:30:30.140
[Guest]: because you would have to then take on anyone who offered. But the say the women who were

00:30:30.140 --> 00:30:36.000
[Guest]: on the higher echelons of the community, they definitely exercise that choice. That's very

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:42.320
[Guest]: well known. So, you know, they rejected lovers, they took on lovers. So, yes, I mean, there

00:30:42.320 --> 00:30:51.880
[Guest]: was a certain sense, a certain autonomous lifestyle, I'd say, that one sees there. And

00:30:51.880 --> 00:30:58.520
[Guest]: which also, I think, gets reflected in the pursuit of their art practice. That's an argument

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:05.120
[Guest]: that I've made, that actually the Thumri and Dadra, etc, that we hear, which is from the

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:12.560
[Guest]: Thawar's voice, that reflects a certain kind of autonomous living lifestyle, a certain

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:21.040
[Amit Varma]: openness of being. And a really telling illustration of the centrality of women in the Thawar community

00:31:21.040 --> 00:31:24.320
[Amit Varma]: was an anecdote at the start of your book, where you talk about how your protagonist

00:31:24.320 --> 00:31:29.380
[Amit Varma]: shows you this family portrait of generations of her family, her aunts and grandmothers

00:31:29.380 --> 00:31:33.840
[Amit Varma]: and grandaunts and all that. And the family portrait is entirely women. And you point

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:39.560
[Amit Varma]: out in contrast, on how a traditional family portrait and any other family portrait is

00:31:39.560 --> 00:31:44.480
[Guest]: mostly men. My father's family portraits, they're just such few women, and they're not

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:49.520
[Guest]: part of the main portraits at all. So, you know, the so called official family portrait

00:31:49.520 --> 00:31:56.200
[Guest]: has all these men, but the women are not there. Except much later now, that's only but that

00:31:56.200 --> 00:32:03.080
[Guest]: happens only by the 60s or so, where then women start making an entry into family portraits,

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:09.480
[Guest]: but not earlier than that. But yes, I mean, in Thawar households, you know, you have these

00:32:09.480 --> 00:32:17.120
[Guest]: walls and you have these photographs. And just women, you know, just my aunt, my great

00:32:17.120 --> 00:32:25.200
[Guest]: aunt, my mother, my grandmother, and there are no men present. So it is a very telling.

00:32:25.200 --> 00:32:31.920
[Guest]: Men are there, they are part of the household. But the kind of status that they have is pretty

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:40.840
[Guest]: much what women enjoy in patriarchal households. And, you know, one of the things that sort

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:47.400
[Amit Varma]: of your book talks a lot about is the extensive training in the arts that the wives go through,

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:52.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, the traditions of the Bol Banao Thumri, Hori, Chaiti, Kajri, Dadra, the association

00:32:52.920 --> 00:32:57.940
[Amit Varma]: of the Kathak with the wives and all that. And at one point you say, quote, besides long

00:32:57.940 --> 00:33:02.120
[Amit Varma]: and arduous training in music and dance, in order to be successful, the wives had to be

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:06.520
[Amit Varma]: educated in a range of other skills, such as a grounding in literature and politics,

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:11.640
[Amit Varma]: as well as knowledge of the intricacies of social etiquette, and of erotic stimulation.

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:16.520
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And I have a couple of questions here. One is, how are the arts being looked

00:33:16.520 --> 00:33:21.720
[Amit Varma]: at by all these people? Like today, the arts are something relatively respectable, that

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:26.320
[Amit Varma]: if you, you know, know a woman who's a writer or a singer or whatever is very respectable,

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:31.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, Lata Mangeshkar is absolutely revered. How were the arts looked at back then? And

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:37.800
[Amit Varma]: was there a reason that it was, you know, more the province of the wives, so to say,

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:45.120
[Amit Varma]: and looked at by whom? Looked at in a general social sense. Okay, by society, by society,

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:49.200
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, you have women in the in the wife communities, they are being trained in

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:53.600
[Amit Varma]: all of those arts, but there is not so much of that happening outside of it. It almost

00:33:53.600 --> 00:34:00.080
[Amit Varma]: seems happening outside. Yeah, it is almost as if it is restricted to them. And the second

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:04.560
[Amit Varma]: sense that, you know, I got from the paragraph I read out, for example, is that all of this,

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:08.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, training in the arts, training in literature, training in practices of seduction

00:34:08.920 --> 00:34:13.160
[Amit Varma]: is all a means to an end, you have to get a patron, there's an economic imperative at

00:34:13.160 --> 00:34:21.320
[Guest]: the bottom of it. I think there's this definite shift in the ways in which the arts get constructed

00:34:21.320 --> 00:34:30.320
[Guest]: and looked upon from the, say, the early 20th century, with the coming on of cultural nationalism.

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:37.040
[Guest]: And then there's this entire focus upon our ancient culture, which kind of starts, you

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:44.640
[Guest]: know, it's part of a certain kind of nationalism, and defining a certain kind of an Indianness.

00:34:44.640 --> 00:34:49.960
[Guest]: So that makes cultural expression more respectable. So where, where, yes, music and dance of a

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:55.720
[Guest]: certain kind, but then again, that there's a problem there, because music and dance of

00:34:55.720 --> 00:35:01.760
[Guest]: a certain kind is acceptable and not of another kind. I'll come to that later. But I think

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:08.120
[Guest]: that if you read, you know, any of the writings before that, and even if you talk to the older

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:13.280
[Guest]: people in the community, even now, I mean, not that they came from that century, they

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:20.400
[Guest]: didn't pretty much. But I mean, they carry certain oral memories and traditions far more.

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:28.840
[Guest]: I sense a very, matter of fact, robust dealing with the arts. You know, it's not like these

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:37.280
[Guest]: rarefied deities, sangeet toh puja ke liye hai, you know, that whatever, sangeet sadhana

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:44.280
[Guest]: or, you don't hear that, at least from within the community. Music is terribly important,

00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:49.240
[Guest]: and not just as a means of livelihood. I mean, sure, it was their livelihood, but it's also

00:35:49.240 --> 00:35:54.800
[Guest]: the ways in which it defines them. So there is a, their own sense of being gets defined

00:35:54.800 --> 00:36:02.080
[Guest]: as musician. So I think the ways in which they look at music is so, so subliminal that

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:08.080
[Guest]: it's also defies easy categorization or definition. I mean, even if they, I mean, I've tried to

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.160
[Guest]: talk to a lot of women about it, and then they'll tell you things like, they'll give

00:36:12.160 --> 00:36:19.680
[Guest]: you anecdotes to explain to you what music means to them. And each one of them is important,

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:24.360
[Guest]: you know, I mean, in terms of this woman who told me that how, you know, she got this patron

00:36:24.360 --> 00:36:29.440
[Guest]: and who, who loved her so much and so deeply, and he wanted to make a respectable woman

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:34.720
[Guest]: out of her. And so he took her away and he said, now you don't have to dance and sing

00:36:34.720 --> 00:36:39.800
[Guest]: for a living. And he looked after her and he was true to his promise. He did look after

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:46.800
[Guest]: her and all of that. And she had children from him. Things went, were going fine, but

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:53.160
[Guest]: she started falling ill and she went into a deep depression. She was just terribly ill.

00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:59.040
[Guest]: And and then finally no medicine worked. And then, you know, and this is like a tale that

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:04.920
[Guest]: gets told by a lot of sources. It's one of those apocryphal tales, which a lot of tawafs

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:09.560
[Guest]: will tell you. It's also attributed to Begum Akhtar. The same thing happened to Begum Akhtar.

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:14.480
[Guest]: But then a lot of other lesser tawafs will also tell you that and take that story for

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:19.520
[Guest]: themselves. I think the importance is not whether this happened or doesn't happen. I

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:25.800
[Guest]: think it's what's, what is it telling you? It's telling you that for all, you know, the

00:37:25.800 --> 00:37:34.640
[Guest]: music is like, this is saans ki tarah hai. It's your breath. And so, so all the respectability

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:41.880
[Guest]: and status that they could get in exchange. This story explains that how actually without

00:37:41.880 --> 00:37:48.080
[Guest]: music you die, you know, and you die a spiritual death, if not a physical death. Although in

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:53.600
[Guest]: these stories, it's like I was dying physically too, because it's just shriveling up in within

00:37:53.600 --> 00:38:00.720
[Guest]: myself. So I think that to me is a very powerful indicator of what music means. But it's not

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:08.320
[Guest]: necessarily imbued with the kind of spiritual connotations that music gets imbued by, say,

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:13.920
[Guest]: by early 20th century, under the influence of the cultural nationalist. I mean, the community

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:18.920
[Guest]: of musicians saw it that way. I think pretty much even in terms of writing, in terms of

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:25.000
[Guest]: society and patrons, music is of course, you know, valorized, validated musicians are made

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:32.320
[Guest]: much of. Patronage of musicians indicates a certain kind of your good taste and status

00:38:32.320 --> 00:38:40.520
[Guest]: and adds, you know, kind of a certain respectability to your position, etc. It's prestige. But

00:38:40.520 --> 00:38:50.680
[Guest]: music and gavaiyas, you know, there is also a certain kind of disrepute attached to it.

00:38:50.680 --> 00:38:57.000
[Guest]: You know, it's like, there is, if you, and I think that has to do very much with a certain

00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:04.320
[Guest]: fear and a certain construction of, this is my understanding of masculinity. And which

00:39:04.320 --> 00:39:13.440
[Guest]: is that, you know, indulgence in music, in ras, as they say, jo ras mein lean hona, that's

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:22.080
[Guest]: all very well. So whether it is music or whether it is the beauty of a woman, love, you know,

00:39:22.080 --> 00:39:30.200
[Guest]: all of those things, to be an aesthete is something of course, which is preferable and

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:39.720
[Guest]: which is much looked up to. But if as a man you lose yourself into that, then it is doom

00:39:39.720 --> 00:39:51.080
[Guest]: for you. So there is a certain kind of a cautionary note always there in terms of be a good patron,

00:39:51.080 --> 00:40:00.800
[Guest]: be a judicious patron. If you kind of go completely enraptured by it, then you spell doom for

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:08.920
[Guest]: yourself, for your household, for business, for dharma. And that holds true, I think both

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:17.880
[Guest]: for, you know, I mean, pretty much within the, you know, Hindus and Muslims, upper classes,

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:24.440
[Guest]: there is that certain, and I think you in Mughal writing, again, the ideal Mirza, who's

00:40:24.440 --> 00:40:30.520
[Guest]: the Mughal aristocrat, the ideal Mirza, he is an aesthete, he will patronize artists,

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:36.080
[Guest]: but he will also patronize, you know, wrestlers and he will patronize this and he'll patronize

00:40:36.080 --> 00:40:43.880
[Guest]: that. But he shouldn't get completely so enraptured that he loses sense of his duties and responsibilities.

00:40:43.880 --> 00:40:51.320
[Guest]: This is pretty much the same thing as the Kartas of a Hindu household. You know, if

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:57.080
[Guest]: you have the means, certainly indulge in the finer things, but don't get so enraptured

00:40:57.080 --> 00:41:03.480
[Guest]: that it brings doom to your household. And you have so many cautionary tales about that.

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:09.800
[Guest]: So I think that that is the certain role, the certain place that the arts occupied,

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:16.200
[Guest]: where arts are very well, and they are marker of your status of, you know, the status of

00:41:16.200 --> 00:41:21.040
[Guest]: the patron. Because they were based so much on individual patronage, without individual

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:30.320
[Guest]: patronage, arts could not flourish. But arts did not define in totality, your sense of

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:37.080
[Guest]: identity of being whatever you were, in all. I mean, for the artist, yes. Not in the way,

00:41:37.080 --> 00:41:42.440
[Guest]: for instance, by early 20th century, you have the arts, which start defining a certain notion

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:50.040
[Guest]: of Indianness, for instance. Before that, there's also a very robust kind of ways in

00:41:50.040 --> 00:41:55.080
[Guest]: which arts are looked at, like they're not rarefied. So you have this thing about, you

00:41:55.080 --> 00:42:01.480
[Guest]: know, when now in early 20th century writing, there's this whole big difference being made

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:09.200
[Guest]: between classical music, and so called lowly popular music. You see, writing before that,

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:14.280
[Guest]: that kind of difference is not made. Also, in terms of the singers themselves, I mean,

00:42:14.280 --> 00:42:20.040
[Guest]: not that we have too much of oral record of it, because recordings come in only by early

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:25.280
[Guest]: 20th century. But in the early recordings, you have singers who are pretty much singing

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:35.720
[Guest]: a whole medley of stuff. And not just very consciously raga based, you know, music. So,

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:39.780
[Guest]: I don't know if I've answered your question. But I think there are shifts that take place

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:47.120
[Guest]: by early 20th century, under the imperative of nationalism, you know, and which then the

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:51.760
[Guest]: arts get start getting defined in a certain way, which is how we receive them now, how

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:59.080
[Guest]: we perceive them now. That's not necessarily something that is shared, you know, pre nationalism.

00:42:59.080 --> 00:43:04.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's a fascinating point you made about, you know, that conception of masculinity,

00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:09.800
[Amit Varma]: which I'll sit back and process gradually, where it almost seems that you're drawing

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:16.440
[Amit Varma]: an analogue between the arts and the wives, where men are supposed to patronize both,

00:43:16.440 --> 00:43:22.000
[Amit Varma]: but not get carried away and give themselves over to both would that be? Yeah, I mean,

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:29.640
[Guest]: the arts are often symbolized, you know, as beautiful women also, they come in that shape.

00:43:29.640 --> 00:43:35.040
[Guest]: So it's the musicians, I mean, the wives, yes. But even male musician, I mean, the fact

00:43:35.040 --> 00:43:41.280
[Guest]: is that you have to maintain a basically the whole emphasis was on maintaining knowing

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:47.840
[Guest]: how to maintain a judicious balance of being an aesthete, but also being a householder

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:54.280
[Guest]: and a responsible householder. And that has to be balanced. Now that that kind of worldview

00:43:54.280 --> 00:44:02.120
[Guest]: changes with the coming in of cultural nationalism. And so you have, you know, music, for instance,

00:44:02.120 --> 00:44:09.880
[Guest]: music now starts defining the contours of Indian identity. And you know, pride of a

00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:14.520
[Guest]: certain nationalist pride in being Indian. So and that carries with it a whole lot of

00:44:14.520 --> 00:44:20.480
[Guest]: baggage, because then certain kind of music becomes acceptable. A lot of other kind of

00:44:20.480 --> 00:44:28.640
[Guest]: music is not acceptable. Certain musicians are acceptable. Certain musicians, many musicians

00:44:28.640 --> 00:44:36.560
[Guest]: really in which also includes all the wives and the devdasis who you know, who are seen

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:44.200
[Guest]: to embody a certain an illicit sexuality. And, you know, their art practice is based

00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:51.240
[Guest]: on pleasure seeking. Now, that is not something which is very acceptable to the cultural nationalists

00:44:51.240 --> 00:44:56.600
[Guest]: who are imbuing the arts with these all these spiritual connotations, you know, of some

00:44:56.600 --> 00:45:04.240
[Guest]: higher purpose and higher being and so those things change. And so, you know, in that process,

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:08.840
[Guest]: exactly not just the colonialists who give the wives who gave the wives, you know, a

00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:15.080
[Guest]: big kick, the bigger portions of stigmatization came actually from our very own nationalists.

00:45:15.080 --> 00:45:20.280
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out in your book, our nationalists were actually educated by the British in the

00:45:20.280 --> 00:45:24.640
[Amit Varma]: British system. So, you know, they did pick up some interesting British liberal values,

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:29.680
[Amit Varma]: but they also picked up this kind of sense of morality. One question that struck me repeatedly

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:37.280
[Amit Varma]: while sort of reading a book was about the wives sense of themselves, in the sense that

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:41.600
[Amit Varma]: if I take the very cynical view that you may disagree with, but if I take the very cynical

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:47.320
[Amit Varma]: view for a moment, that all human interactions are transactional, and that whatever else

00:45:47.320 --> 00:45:52.040
[Amit Varma]: that appears non transactional is essentially a veneer, we are rationalizing it. So there's

00:45:52.040 --> 00:45:55.880
[Amit Varma]: a kind of women who are living traditional lives, and their housewives and they're doing

00:45:55.880 --> 00:46:01.400
[Amit Varma]: whatever, in some sense, they are self delusional. But I would imagine that the wives would be

00:46:01.400 --> 00:46:06.280
[Amit Varma]: less delusional, because they would have a much clearer sense of the transactional nature

00:46:06.280 --> 00:46:11.100
[Amit Varma]: of relationships of the sort of role that they play within, you know, the patriarchal

00:46:11.100 --> 00:46:15.480
[Amit Varma]: system that they are part of. So does that make sense to you that there is a greater

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:20.720
[Amit Varma]: sense of self awareness there. And this also struck me like you quoted one the wife is

00:46:20.720 --> 00:46:27.440
[Amit Varma]: telling you, tum bahut bholi ho aur bahut bevakoof bhi ho. And this also seems to be,

00:46:27.440 --> 00:46:31.840
[Guest]: you know, an expression of a certain kind. I think that has to do with she was commenting

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:37.160
[Guest]: more on my class. And the kind of you know, I mean, you come from a certain class and

00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:44.040
[Guest]: you are kind of inured from the harshness of life. And there's a certain naivety that

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:53.080
[Guest]: she presumed that I was coming with. But firstly, I don't think that women who were housebound

00:46:53.080 --> 00:46:58.440
[Amit Varma]: weren't necessarily delusional at all. Necessarily, but it would have helped if they were for

00:46:58.440 --> 00:47:03.320
[Amit Varma]: them to be happy. Yes, they sought their happiness and found their happiness in whatever ways

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:08.520
[Guest]: in which they I'm sure I mean, it's just that so much less is written about from within

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:15.080
[Guest]: the household in terms of, you know, I'm sure they also found their ways of playing patriarchy.

00:47:15.080 --> 00:47:19.800
[Guest]: You have to if you have to survive, whether in a nice way or a bad way, but that's not

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:25.840
[Guest]: the point. The point is that if you have to, it's an unequal relationship. And so people

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:32.280
[Guest]: who are placed in that position on the wrong foot, then they find their ways to play the

00:47:32.280 --> 00:47:39.800
[Guest]: system. So that's because if you see if you were to talk to I mean, you know, I'm not

00:47:39.800 --> 00:47:44.040
[Guest]: talking about the wives, I'm talking about housebound women, and they interest me a great

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:49.520
[Guest]: deal because my own family, for instance, and especially my father's family, pretty

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:55.680
[Guest]: much represented that, you know, it's very patriarchal family and very tradition bound

00:47:55.680 --> 00:48:02.880
[Guest]: to a certain extent. And yet there are all these stories of these grandmothers and grandaunts,

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:09.040
[Guest]: whose word was law. Now, how was their word law? You know, because technically, they did

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:16.200
[Guest]: not enjoy, they did not even have the right to inherit, etc. So how was their word law,

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:21.920
[Guest]: but their word apparently was law. And even none of the men crossed, you know, if they

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:27.720
[Guest]: said some decided something, then even the men could wouldn't go against that. So I think

00:48:27.720 --> 00:48:32.720
[Guest]: that it's a complicated field. It's not that all women could, I think most women had a

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:39.640
[Guest]: shit time and a horrible time. But I think we can't make victims out of everyone. So

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:45.480
[Guest]: and the fact is that the women lived certain lives. And that's for me, that's what I'm

00:48:45.480 --> 00:48:50.920
[Guest]: saying is that as as a documentarian, I mean, that's what has always been interesting. What

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:56.120
[Guest]: were those lives? What did they make of it? How did they look at it? I mean, so I don't

00:48:56.120 --> 00:49:02.360
[Guest]: know, they were delusional at all. Pretty much my might have seen that, man, I'm situated

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:07.680
[Guest]: here. Now I've got to work myself into a certain way. And you know, I mean, they were after

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:18.120
[Guest]: all, there they were in this hive of complicated, really power laden relationships, how to move

00:49:18.120 --> 00:49:23.240
[Guest]: and make your move, it seemed like some elaborate kind of a chess game, if you look at it from

00:49:23.240 --> 00:49:28.720
[Guest]: the outside, and well, they were they played it. So maybe some played it better than the

00:49:28.720 --> 00:49:35.440
[Amit Varma]: others. But no, I think I think my phrasing was clumsy. I wasn't using the term delusional

00:49:35.440 --> 00:49:40.320
[Amit Varma]: as as a way of dissing them. Like my very cynical view is that I think we all need delusions

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:45.100
[Amit Varma]: to survive and we choose our own delusions. You know, some may believe in God or some

00:49:45.100 --> 00:49:50.880
[Amit Varma]: may overemphasize notions of romantic love or whatever. And it seems to me that the wives

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:56.140
[Amit Varma]: by virtue of their position would at least be disabused of some of the typical delusions

00:49:56.140 --> 00:50:00.760
[Guest]: that I think that again would be romanticizing them. Because, you know, the fact is that

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:07.920
[Guest]: yes, there, I think there's maybe a greater awareness than most, in terms of having an

00:50:07.920 --> 00:50:14.160
[Guest]: awareness of the transactional nature of their relationships, which may be many of us. And

00:50:14.160 --> 00:50:20.160
[Guest]: I think especially the middle class, we are uncomfortable admitting that. And so we kind

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:25.800
[Guest]: of say, we put a lot of things to it. But that's the same as sex workers do. There is

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:32.960
[Guest]: a certain and there's a recognition of that, because with the sex worker, for instance,

00:50:32.960 --> 00:50:37.560
[Guest]: comes stripped of everything else, you've got to recognize it for what it is. And I

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:44.520
[Guest]: think with the wives too, what they were very good at, actually was to create illusion.

00:50:44.520 --> 00:50:49.600
[Guest]: So I think that is the interesting point, because, you know, here are women who are

00:50:49.600 --> 00:50:54.600
[Guest]: entering into, well, I will be your lover, you will be my patron, you will maintain me

00:50:54.600 --> 00:51:00.160
[Guest]: the monthly income, blah, blah, blah, you know, it came with a certain ways of being.

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:04.680
[Guest]: And so it was a certain transaction, but it was never stated as such. It was all played

00:51:04.680 --> 00:51:13.640
[Guest]: out as this elaborate love affair. And, you know, which they are in control of. Well,

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:17.600
[Guest]: yes, but which is what they would like to believe that they were always in control.

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:22.480
[Guest]: But believe me, there were a lot of stories, even in this book, there are, where sometimes

00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:27.560
[Guest]: they were not in control. They were human beings, you know, human beings win in love,

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:32.600
[Guest]: lose in love. And I think that's how things go on. So yeah, I wouldn't make them into

00:51:32.600 --> 00:51:37.800
[Guest]: some super women. And that was my endeavor also in the book. They're not that these super

00:51:37.800 --> 00:51:44.120
[Guest]: women who are also clear eyed all the time. Relatively speaking, yes, because the nature

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:49.760
[Guest]: of their relationship with the outside, not within themselves, there is a certain recognition,

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:56.360
[Guest]: because it's also easier to recognize the transactional nature of that relationship.

00:51:56.360 --> 00:52:04.280
[Guest]: Because that's how it takes place. And yes, there is a certain kind of wisdom and smartness

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:07.840
[Guest]: that is there because they are survivors and these are self made women. I think that is

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:13.600
[Guest]: really important. They don't have any padding of, you know, family or someone padding you

00:52:13.600 --> 00:52:20.400
[Guest]: up forget about family, just your class privileges, or where you come from, or, you know, none

00:52:20.400 --> 00:52:28.560
[Guest]: of that. So if you are a survivor, then you know, you cannot afford to be in some delusional

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:36.040
[Guest]: state, you've got to be far more clear eyed, that certainly, but to the extent that for

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:41.160
[Guest]: women who were, I mean, we're talking about the heydays of the Tawaif culture. Yes, there

00:52:41.160 --> 00:52:48.520
[Guest]: were young Tawaifs who also fell in love, and who also stupidly wanted to throw away

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:53.240
[Guest]: their, you know, thriving careers, who fell in love during wrestling matches, as we shall

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:58.360
[Guest]: discuss shortly. And who, well, who, you know, it was just as well that Dilip Singh went

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:03.800
[Guest]: off. Otherwise, she was quite happy to have gone after, she was a young Tawaif. So those

00:53:03.800 --> 00:53:09.320
[Guest]: things happened. I mean, after all, these men and women, love strikes also.

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:13.800
[Amit Varma]: No, it's interesting that the story you mentioned about the Tawaif falling ill because she has

00:53:13.800 --> 00:53:18.600
[Amit Varma]: been separated from her music, seemed poignant to me. And that also seemed to speak to this

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:24.680
[Amit Varma]: point. And I hope I'm not simplifying too much, that whereas they might recognize the

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:29.680
[Amit Varma]: contingent nature of everything else, their relationship with music is not contingent.

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:34.400
[Amit Varma]: Because if you are a musician, there is nothing transactional about that. It's all encompassing.

00:53:34.400 --> 00:53:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, when separated from the one genuine thing in your life, I can sort of

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:45.040
[Guest]: sense where that... No, there are lots. Actually, music is, of course, a very, very, very important

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:51.040
[Guest]: thing. But that's not the only genuine thing in the lives of Tawaifs. You know, their relationships

00:53:51.040 --> 00:53:57.800
[Guest]: with each other, for instance. I mean, the kind of very close relationships that women

00:53:57.800 --> 00:54:04.680
[Guest]: share with each other. Now, that is something and the book has it, you know, except I'm

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:10.200
[Guest]: not that I'm not underlining it. But the fact is, their primary relationships are with women,

00:54:10.200 --> 00:54:15.760
[Guest]: with other women. Women with their own family, their sisters or their daughters or nieces

00:54:15.760 --> 00:54:22.520
[Guest]: or whatever aunts. Or very often their adopted children. Adopted children, friends, women

00:54:22.520 --> 00:54:29.160
[Guest]: friends from within the community. And these are really intense relationships. So I remember

00:54:29.160 --> 00:54:35.880
[Guest]: one of the women who's now a very good friend. Very early on, I was flicking through her

00:54:35.880 --> 00:54:43.360
[Guest]: photographs and I came across these two photographs of the same woman and with her arm around

00:54:43.360 --> 00:54:49.640
[Guest]: her. And there's something about it. So I said, Who is she? And she said, Yeh humaari

00:54:49.640 --> 00:54:57.040
[Guest]: friend hai. You know, and that seemed okay. Friend, you know, this and she's also a Tawaif

00:54:57.040 --> 00:55:03.640
[Guest]: but from Gaya, not from even the same town. Then over the years, I got to know her. To

00:55:03.640 --> 00:55:07.720
[Guest]: this day, I don't really know the nature of their relationship, whether it's sexual or

00:55:07.720 --> 00:55:13.840
[Guest]: not. I don't know. I don't think it matters. Yeah, because I'm not sure that for her too,

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:20.240
[Guest]: is the kind of woman she is. There's a certain abundance of so much to her, you know, in

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:29.600
[Guest]: terms of the ability to give and the ability to also take. So, I don't know. But yes, I

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:35.680
[Guest]: know why those photographs are there. Because the intensity of that love, that friendship,

00:55:35.680 --> 00:55:42.800
[Guest]: humaari friend hai. It really struck to me. I can't explain it, but it meant so much the

00:55:42.800 --> 00:55:47.160
[Guest]: way she said it. And of course, then I got to know her and I met the other woman. And

00:55:47.160 --> 00:55:53.680
[Guest]: I know how close they are. I mean, it's like, you know that if this woman, if there's something

00:55:53.680 --> 00:56:00.520
[Guest]: plaguing her, then the other woman will definitely know. You know, she will know what is the

00:56:00.520 --> 00:56:07.600
[Guest]: real issue. So, those are also relationships, which are very, very important. Actually,

00:56:07.600 --> 00:56:12.160
[Guest]: family relationships, it is the other part which is rarely talked about, which is there

00:56:12.160 --> 00:56:18.800
[Guest]: in the book. Of course, book talks locates them in their family. We make this categorization

00:56:18.800 --> 00:56:24.840
[Guest]: between family women and tawaifs. Family women are respectable women and tawaifs are well

00:56:24.840 --> 00:56:31.200
[Guest]: tawaifs. And somehow, in popular culture, in cinema, tawaifs are always shown. You know,

00:56:31.200 --> 00:56:37.880
[Guest]: these alienated creatures from nowhere almost, with no one. And who've come and then there

00:56:37.880 --> 00:56:46.440
[Guest]: is some like conniving, you know, lady of the, you know, owner of the kota who has either

00:56:46.440 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: kidnapped her or bought her or whatever, whatever. The fact is, they all belong to a close-knit

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:00.080
[Guest]: community and very close-knit families. And those families, and these are women who are

00:57:00.080 --> 00:57:07.480
[Guest]: heading those families, and so carry a huge sense of duty and responsibility. Now, there

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:12.800
[Guest]: are a lot of it is not it. Most of it, I don't see it as transactional at all. It comes out

00:57:12.800 --> 00:57:21.720
[Guest]: of, well, those are givens. It's like, very much like I'm the elder son of the family.

00:57:21.720 --> 00:57:26.920
[Guest]: I've got to do this. So, I've got to do it. And so, you know, you say, well, why do you

00:57:26.920 --> 00:57:33.360
[Guest]: have to do this? Why do you have to get your nephews into jobs, who will find jobs? Who

00:57:33.360 --> 00:57:37.720
[Guest]: else will? I have to do it. And until they don't, they have to live with me. So, you

00:57:37.720 --> 00:57:45.640
[Guest]: know, this, in fact, I see in Tawaif households, there's a lot of emphasis on that. These are

00:57:45.640 --> 00:57:53.560
[Guest]: women who are, you know, taking care of very extended families, very, very extended families.

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:59.840
[Guest]: A lot of them, you know, active, fairly parasitical in nature, because this is one woman earning

00:57:59.840 --> 00:58:05.320
[Guest]: or maximum two women earning, and everyone just kind of living. But that's the nature

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:12.720
[Guest]: of those families used to be. Now, of course, it's changed. But there's nothing there. Now,

00:58:12.720 --> 00:58:18.280
[Guest]: whether it's delusional or, you know, it's pretty much the same as family, you know,

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:22.560
[Amit Varma]: as we see it in the other families. Fair enough. And a lot of your book does come

00:58:22.560 --> 00:58:27.120
[Guest]: across as if it's just a story of another family. And there's so much intimacy. Because

00:58:27.120 --> 00:58:32.920
[Guest]: we don't see them. The writing, actually, I think a lot of times, that point doesn't

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:38.920
[Guest]: come across. The book, of course, is located in the family. These are families. And also

00:58:38.920 --> 00:58:46.920
[Guest]: the, you know, the ways in this family quarrels, family tensions, but also closeness and estrangements,

00:58:46.920 --> 00:58:54.040
[Guest]: but then reproach, all of that, pretty much of what Indian families are all about. So,

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:58.640
[Guest]: except that here, it's not really the same, because here it's the women who are actually

00:58:58.640 --> 00:59:06.360
[Guest]: the drivers. And in those ways, actually, certain dynamics change very much. But the

00:59:06.360 --> 00:59:11.080
[Guest]: expectations and the responsibilities and duties, they are pretty much played out in

00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:14.360
[Amit Varma]: a similar manner. True. Let's take a quick commercial break.

00:59:14.360 --> 00:59:18.160
[Amit Varma]: And after the commercial break, we'll come back and talk about one of the most fascinating

00:59:18.160 --> 00:59:23.000
[Amit Varma]: characters in your book. That's Thurman Beebe and her story, which also I think, you know,

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:27.400
[Amit Varma]: her life seems to be set just as the sands are shifting. And, you know, so much is changing

00:59:27.400 --> 00:59:31.360
[Amit Varma]: for the wives and indeed for India. So I found it quite fascinating. Let's take a quick commercial

00:59:31.360 --> 00:59:36.360
[Amit Varma]: break. If you're listening to the scene in the unseen,

00:59:36.360 --> 00:59:40.800
[Amit Varma]: it means you like listening to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case,

