[Amit Varma]: by Manu Pillay. Download the Storytel app or visit Storytel.com. Remember, there's Storytel

01:00:43.880 --> 01:00:50.680
[Amit Varma]: with a single L. Storytel.com. Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with

01:00:50.680 --> 01:00:55.900
[Amit Varma]: Sabha Dewan about a fantastic book, Tawaif Nama and indeed all her work on exploring

01:00:55.900 --> 01:01:01.440
[Amit Varma]: the history of the Tawaif community. And you know, what I loved about your book also is

01:01:01.440 --> 01:01:06.040
[Amit Varma]: that it's not a boring retelling of this happened in history that happened, but it's got all

01:01:06.040 --> 01:01:11.200
[Amit Varma]: these wonderful vivid characters who come to life. And one of them, of course, is a

01:01:11.200 --> 01:01:18.920
[Amit Varma]: character of Dharman Bibi. And Dharman Bibi is not just a young Tawaif, she's also a wrestler.

01:01:18.920 --> 01:01:23.800
[Amit Varma]: So tell us a little bit about, you know, her early life and what her journey reveals about,

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:32.480
[Guest]: you know, those times. And I think, see, Dharman Bibi is an early 19th century Tawaif. And

01:01:32.480 --> 01:01:43.640
[Guest]: so, now she is important because she represents just a certain glimpse of, you know, the kind

01:01:43.640 --> 01:01:51.280
[Guest]: of the role that Tawaifs played or, you know, the kind of access that they had to power

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:57.400
[Guest]: and the way that they were being looked at just before 1857. You know, in fact, the whole

01:01:57.400 --> 01:02:06.000
[Guest]: thing builds up to 1857, you know, the rebellion of 1857. And therefore, when this story came

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:14.200
[Guest]: to me and, you know, this family, they talked about their great, great, great grandmother,

01:02:14.200 --> 01:02:22.320
[Guest]: as like completely, you know, taken in, because A, I had not come across a continuous family

01:02:22.320 --> 01:02:28.480
[Guest]: history that went that long back. And B, she is just lovely, you know, and then there was

01:02:28.480 --> 01:02:34.400
[Guest]: a mention of her even in the Gazetteer. I found it. So I said, wow, I mean, she's absolutely

01:02:34.400 --> 01:02:40.000
[Guest]: lovely. But she is not the only, you know, the thing about being a wrestler, strange

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:47.640
[Guest]: as it may sound, it actually there were other Tawaifs of later vintage, who also, I'm not

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:54.680
[Guest]: too sure what the connection was. But I think maybe it's like physical regimen or exercise.

01:02:54.680 --> 01:03:01.040
[Guest]: You're really fit, at least. Probably, because I've come across at least

01:03:01.040 --> 01:03:11.840
[Guest]: two or three instances of, you know, women of Tawaifs, either being interested in wrestling.

01:03:11.840 --> 01:03:16.880
[Guest]: Interested in wrestling, fine, you are and the patrons of wrestlers, which also you don't

01:03:16.880 --> 01:03:25.600
[Guest]: kind of associate, but yes, like, but also being in doing wrestling, knowing wrestling,

01:03:25.600 --> 01:03:31.960
[Guest]: knowing this Lathbazi. So, you know, these swordmanship, etc. It's very strange. That

01:03:31.960 --> 01:03:37.400
[Guest]: kind of goes out then. By about late 19th century, one doesn't find these references

01:03:37.400 --> 01:03:43.960
[Guest]: as much. But in Banaras, I have come across. In fact, if I'm not mistaken, even the great

01:03:43.960 --> 01:03:51.600
[Guest]: Vidyadhari Bai, who is the great Thumri singer, I think, yes, she was very fond of, you know,

01:03:51.600 --> 01:03:57.440
[Guest]: wrestling, or she could do wrestling herself. I'm not, I can't remember that. But I think

01:03:57.440 --> 01:04:03.960
[Guest]: doing her, something about it. If you look at it, it's also about a certain mobility

01:04:03.960 --> 01:04:11.160
[Guest]: and freedom of space of accessing. See, if you are wrestling, or you are, you know, doing

01:04:11.160 --> 01:04:19.680
[Guest]: Lathbazi and all of that, and also horse riding, then there is an access to open spaces. You

01:04:19.680 --> 01:04:26.160
[Guest]: know, there's a person who has enjoys that kind of freedom to access and freedom of movement.

01:04:26.160 --> 01:04:33.040
[Amit Varma]: It is not exactly speaking of that, really. And one of the memorable scenes in your book,

01:04:33.040 --> 01:04:37.840
[Amit Varma]: and it's interesting, I should call it scenes because you are, of course, a filmmaker. And

01:04:37.840 --> 01:04:41.720
[Amit Varma]: this scene seemed so cinematic to me, like if ever a web series is made, this could really

01:04:41.720 --> 01:04:46.400
[Amit Varma]: be a pivotal scene. And the pilot episode is that wrestling match, where you describe

01:04:46.400 --> 01:04:51.680
[Amit Varma]: how this wrestler Dilip Singh is just beating all comers. And then at one point where he's

01:04:51.680 --> 01:04:55.840
[Amit Varma]: beaten everyone, he's like, you know, does anyone care to challenge me? Does anyone have

01:04:55.840 --> 01:05:00.560
[Amit Varma]: the courage? And this young 19 year old wife, which is of course, Dharmanbhai, has a self

01:05:00.560 --> 01:05:04.960
[Amit Varma]: confidence to say that I will challenge you. And then she challenges him. And then that

01:05:04.960 --> 01:05:11.280
[Amit Varma]: wrestling scene itself is so tinged with the erotic, that they are actually wrestling with

01:05:11.280 --> 01:05:17.760
[Amit Varma]: each other. And it's a clash where eventually, none of them win. And then they eventually

01:05:17.760 --> 01:05:25.200
[Amit Varma]: become lovers. And all of that was sort of incredibly fascinating. And one wonders that

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:29.840
[Amit Varma]: the people who are telling you the story, her great, great, great granddaughter, you

01:05:29.840 --> 01:05:33.960
[Amit Varma]: know, in their imagining, how is all of this happening? Are they romanticizing it? Are

01:05:33.960 --> 01:05:37.960
[Amit Varma]: they sort of building it up? Are you feeling in certain blanks yourself?

01:05:37.960 --> 01:05:44.120
[Guest]: Yeah, I think what I was interested in, was in the ways in which the story was being told

01:05:44.120 --> 01:05:50.160
[Guest]: to me. Because I think after all, these are stories that are coming down so many generations,

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:55.600
[Guest]: there surely must be additions in them, which I was open to. And my interest was not that

01:05:55.600 --> 01:06:03.360
[Guest]: this has to be some authentic, that each part of the story has to be validated. Because

01:06:03.360 --> 01:06:09.760
[Guest]: my interest in these stories was of the Tawaifs telling their own stories. I mean, see what

01:06:09.760 --> 01:06:14.440
[Guest]: is important to them in the telling of the story about, say, Dharman Bibi.

01:06:14.440 --> 01:06:17.920
[Guest]: And even anything they've added would actually be revelatory.

01:06:17.920 --> 01:06:26.440
[Guest]: Absolutely. So that is why I was so interested in hearing from them, the stories about, you

01:06:26.440 --> 01:06:32.440
[Guest]: know, these women in their families. Because that points towards the ways in what are the

01:06:32.440 --> 01:06:39.840
[Guest]: things that they valorize? What are the things that are important? Where is the erotic? And

01:06:39.840 --> 01:06:45.760
[Guest]: erotic, I realized pretty much, could also reside in a wrestling match. And in fact,

01:06:45.760 --> 01:06:51.880
[Guest]: it was very erotic. You know, when I could see immense possibilities there. It's something

01:06:51.880 --> 01:06:58.680
[Guest]: if I had been just presented, if I had to think of it, maybe for a moment, I'd be a

01:06:58.680 --> 01:07:03.880
[Guest]: little bit flummoxed. But once I was told that story, definitely, yes, of course, an

01:07:03.880 --> 01:07:09.480
[Guest]: extremely erotic moment, and charged moment. In fact, the image that came to mind is in

01:07:09.480 --> 01:07:13.440
[Amit Varma]: the film Ghosts, Patrick Swayze and Demi Moore, and they're doing that sculpting bit. And

01:07:13.440 --> 01:07:18.640
[Guest]: that's an erotic moment in the act of what is otherwise something totally unerotic. Yeah.

01:07:18.640 --> 01:07:24.640
[Amit Varma]: And I was also, you know, there's also this sort of fantastical element in your book in

01:07:24.640 --> 01:07:28.640
[Amit Varma]: the stories, which are obviously coming through from what the stories that you're being told.

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:33.760
[Amit Varma]: Right. And you're reproducing them, for example, much later when Dharman BB, you know, she

01:07:33.760 --> 01:07:38.000
[Amit Varma]: and her husband, Kuber Singh have rebelled, and they're on the run and all of that. And

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:41.840
[Amit Varma]: she's hiding in a temple and she's giving birth to twins. And every element of that

01:07:41.840 --> 01:07:47.880
[Amit Varma]: little bit is obviously not true, but obviously also true in a certain way. For example, every

01:07:47.880 --> 01:07:52.080
[Amit Varma]: time the English try to enter as a lightning strike, and she is protected, the Devi is

01:07:52.080 --> 01:07:57.880
[Guest]: protecting her. That's how they read it. Yeah. And see, for me, I think that's the documentary

01:07:57.880 --> 01:08:06.200
[Guest]: part of the filmmaker part of me. I realized pretty early as a filmmaker, documentary filmmaker,

01:08:06.200 --> 01:08:13.280
[Guest]: that reality is very relative. You know, in terms of what is reality, it could be a slippery

01:08:13.280 --> 01:08:20.880
[Guest]: creature. And your reality is not the same as mine. And for me, what is more important

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:27.480
[Guest]: is in terms of the ways in which a story is told. It's not the whether it happened or

01:08:27.480 --> 01:08:34.280
[Guest]: it didn't happen. It's actually, ultimately, what is the story telling me? What is it pointing

01:08:34.280 --> 01:08:41.480
[Guest]: me towards? So there is this kind of element of magical realism, which is there throughout

01:08:41.480 --> 01:08:48.280
[Guest]: the book. Now, here is a community that, you know, is also very steeped in, by the way,

01:08:48.280 --> 01:08:57.360
[Guest]: in Sufi worship, and then that cuts across Hindus and Muslims. And there is a ways in

01:08:57.360 --> 01:09:04.560
[Guest]: which that they, I think that could be true of a lot of other Indians. It's of looking

01:09:04.560 --> 01:09:12.280
[Guest]: at realities, where this kind of, you know, this junct between what we call the fantastical

01:09:12.280 --> 01:09:19.520
[Guest]: and the real world necessarily does not exist. So what is, you know, the, there are ghosts

01:09:19.520 --> 01:09:25.480
[Guest]: who enter your, you know, world, and they are also creatures. And they are also, there

01:09:25.480 --> 01:09:30.880
[Guest]: are Sufi saints who are your benefactors. And they are people almost, I mean, they become

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:37.920
[Guest]: like characters in your story. And they are like these, your family elders also almost

01:09:37.920 --> 01:09:44.680
[Guest]: taking care of you. So I pretty much realized that, I mean, this was an amazing treasure

01:09:44.680 --> 01:09:54.400
[Guest]: trove of stories. And I didn't want to reduce, be reductionist and you know, because I think,

01:09:54.400 --> 01:10:00.720
[Guest]: for me, the way they were told to me, I was interested in telling them as they were, without

01:10:00.720 --> 01:10:08.400
[Guest]: passing judgment, because how can I claim that my reality is of a superior nature or

01:10:08.400 --> 01:10:15.480
[Guest]: more real, I mean, or my idea of reality. There's no ways in which there's certain arrogance

01:10:15.480 --> 01:10:20.480
[Guest]: that I could be speaking from that. No, I agree entirely. And for me, for instance,

01:10:20.480 --> 01:10:25.880
[Guest]: that you know, the whole bit about when a Dharman baby is giving birth to the baby girls

01:10:25.880 --> 01:10:34.080
[Guest]: in the sanctuary of Mundeshwari Devi's temple. Here's a Muslim Tawaif. This is a narrative

01:10:34.080 --> 01:10:41.720
[Guest]: which flies in the face of colonial writing. And also later, even the, you know, the Hindu

01:10:41.720 --> 01:10:47.160
[Guest]: nationalist writing. It shows you how natural our syncreticness is. So, and here are these

01:10:47.160 --> 01:10:53.960
[Guest]: Muslim Tawaifs, three generations down or four generations down, telling me that story

01:10:53.960 --> 01:11:00.400
[Guest]: about so it is their telling of the story that I'm going on. And where Mundeshwari naturally

01:11:00.400 --> 01:11:06.800
[Guest]: becomes foster mother almost. She's Devi. She is the mother. She's mother goddess. She

01:11:06.800 --> 01:11:11.600
[Guest]: has to be Dharman's mother. And she will have to protect Dharman and Dharman becomes her

01:11:11.600 --> 01:11:18.080
[Guest]: daughter. And this Dharman, this great warrior, the wife warrior is now at her most vulnerable

01:11:18.080 --> 01:11:24.240
[Guest]: because you know, she's giving birth and she's helpless and the enemy is outside. And so

01:11:24.240 --> 01:11:31.000
[Guest]: of course, she's in the embrace of her mother, who then takes care of her and protects her.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:36.640
[Guest]: When I heard of it, I actually had goosebumps, you know, because and then they attribute

01:11:36.640 --> 01:11:45.000
[Guest]: and says, you see, Sadabahar, don't forget, she was one of the twins, the daughters, Dharman's

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:52.800
[Guest]: daughter. And Sadabahar, you know, has this mystical destiny. And she's also very fearless

01:11:52.800 --> 01:12:00.200
[Guest]: in many ways. And they said that Sadabahar was after all born under Mundeshwari's gaze.

01:12:00.200 --> 01:12:07.080
[Guest]: And it somehow becomes that, you know, that transmission of a certain energy that happened.

01:12:07.080 --> 01:12:14.480
[Guest]: It's all very fascinating. And this also kind of ruptures this kind of ways in which you

01:12:14.480 --> 01:12:20.560
[Guest]: patriarchy posits the illicit sexuality of the Tawaif and the Devi. You know, Aap ya

01:12:20.560 --> 01:12:27.440
[Guest]: Devi hai, ya patita hai. But here actually the Tawaif is giving birth in the sanctuary

01:12:27.440 --> 01:12:34.800
[Guest]: of the Devi and the Devi becomes the mother. So, of course, I love this story. And it said

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:41.520
[Guest]: so many things to me and provided me with an understanding with the ways in which they

01:12:41.520 --> 01:12:49.320
[Guest]: construct syncreticism and lived syncretism. It's not like a spoken off or romanticized.

01:12:49.320 --> 01:12:55.800
[Guest]: This is like very matter of fact, the way this story was told to me. And I just hope

01:12:55.800 --> 01:13:03.120
[Guest]: that the readers also kind of give them that kind of peep.

01:13:03.120 --> 01:13:06.720
[Amit Varma]: That's one of the things that made your book such a fun read is that you have allowed these

01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:11.080
[Amit Varma]: stories to sort of, like you said, you just documented them. And it strikes me in a way

01:13:11.080 --> 01:13:16.240
[Amit Varma]: that all histories are in some sense or the other mythologies. And, you know, the fact

01:13:16.240 --> 01:13:21.320
[Amit Varma]: that a lot of this history is actually almost oral history is coming down through the generations.

01:13:21.320 --> 01:13:26.040
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, all these layers are getting added on and there were some beautifully filmy

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:31.480
[Amit Varma]: layers and all this. But, you know, in her life also, there are these sort of, you see

01:13:31.480 --> 01:13:36.040
[Amit Varma]: society and the economy and politics changing as well. You know, for example, in the fact

01:13:36.040 --> 01:13:40.080
[Amit Varma]: that as you pointed out, she was besotted with the Lipsynch, she wanted to be with him.

01:13:40.080 --> 01:13:44.600
[Amit Varma]: But his economic circumstances led him to, you know, follow his brothers into the army

01:13:44.600 --> 01:13:50.960
[Amit Varma]: and he's gone. And then she is being wooed by this man old enough to be her grandfather,

01:13:50.960 --> 01:13:56.360
[Amit Varma]: Kuwar Singh. And at first, he's not willing. And then comes this very filmy element of

01:13:56.360 --> 01:14:01.520
[Amit Varma]: her aunt Zahooran being wooed and poisoned by this Khan Azad Khan, sort of cut a long

01:14:01.520 --> 01:14:06.560
[Amit Varma]: story short. And it's a delightful filmy story. Again, she dies and she gets into this marriage.

01:14:06.560 --> 01:14:10.560
[Amit Varma]: And it's a wonderful, beautiful, loving marriage, which is, you know, it's not a marriage, it's

01:14:10.560 --> 01:14:14.320
[Amit Varma]: a partnership. It's a partnership. She's a mistress, but it's almost like a marriage

01:14:14.320 --> 01:14:20.280
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that she's the official sort of, I mean, there's another very nice story

01:14:20.280 --> 01:14:25.480
[Amit Varma]: you tell about how this English official comes to Kuwar Singh's house and, you know, other

01:14:25.480 --> 01:14:30.320
[Amit Varma]: Tawaifs are performing for him. And obviously, Dharman is at an elevated level being the

01:14:30.320 --> 01:14:33.840
[Amit Varma]: mistress of this man, and she's not expected to perform. But then the Englishman says,

01:14:33.840 --> 01:14:38.080
[Amit Varma]: no, I want to see her. And he can't piss off the Englishman because his economic fortunes

01:14:38.080 --> 01:14:44.600
[Amit Varma]: are going down and he depends on the British. And she performs and he's getting to sort

01:14:44.600 --> 01:14:50.560
[Amit Varma]: of carried away by this. And I'll quote from your book, Dharman seethed silently. This

01:14:50.560 --> 01:14:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Virangi, foreigner, was behaving as if she, the leading Tawaif of Shahabad, was a humble

01:14:55.720 --> 01:15:02.320
[Amit Varma]: Nachinia, a low placed dancer, or worse, a poor prostitute selling sex to English soldiers.

01:15:02.320 --> 01:15:05.960
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And there is again a delightful story about how she keeps piling him with

01:15:05.960 --> 01:15:11.720
[Amit Varma]: drinks and then sends one of her... Gets him so drunk and then... Yeah, sends a maidservant

01:15:11.720 --> 01:15:15.680
[Amit Varma]: dressed in her clothes and the guy doesn't realize the difference, all of which is like

01:15:15.680 --> 01:15:20.760
[Amit Varma]: incredibly filmy. So if Bollywood people are listening to this.

01:15:20.760 --> 01:15:28.160
[Guest]: These stories come down, the book is also pegged into actual research. And, you know,

01:15:28.160 --> 01:15:34.560
[Guest]: I mean, and archival research. And so, which is the part which took a lot of time, but

01:15:34.560 --> 01:15:41.240
[Guest]: actually, to understand a community, how do you understand a community? Yes, the context,

01:15:41.240 --> 01:15:47.120
[Guest]: I was providing and I was working hard on them in researching the political, social

01:15:47.120 --> 01:15:53.520
[Guest]: changing context. You know, this is like the unfolding of India through this Tawaif family

01:15:53.520 --> 01:16:00.800
[Guest]: over 200 years. The thing is that the history of music and musicians in India, especially,

01:16:00.800 --> 01:16:06.840
[Guest]: there's not that much written material. It's very based on oral accounts, oral histories.

01:16:06.840 --> 01:16:13.240
[Guest]: You have to actually depend on those. And you come across actually over and over again,

01:16:13.240 --> 01:16:19.840
[Guest]: you come across very many stories. I make no claims that any of these stories, necessarily,

01:16:19.840 --> 01:16:25.000
[Guest]: it's exactly how it happened. It may or it may not have happened that way. But it's the

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:31.520
[Guest]: family's understanding of their sense of self. They derive their sense of self from these

01:16:31.520 --> 01:16:39.800
[Guest]: stories of their, well, grandmother, aunts, grandaunts. That is what is giving also like,

01:16:39.800 --> 01:16:44.440
[Guest]: you know, getting channelized into their sense of self. And what is that construction? How

01:16:44.440 --> 01:16:48.960
[Guest]: are they constructing these histories? That speaks to me a lot about how the community

01:16:48.960 --> 01:16:56.560
[Guest]: constructs itself, what the community values. It gives me a peep into their ways of being.

01:16:56.560 --> 01:17:02.600
[Guest]: So, you know, some of the stories, whether unbelievable or not, but some of them are

01:17:02.600 --> 01:17:08.800
[Guest]: actually very delightful. And the ones which have the element of, great element of magical

01:17:08.800 --> 01:17:16.120
[Guest]: realism. Later on, there's this story of this, you know, aunt of the protagonist who literally

01:17:16.120 --> 01:17:22.320
[Guest]: loses her way. She has this destiny of being one of the greatest musicians. And it's a

01:17:22.320 --> 01:17:26.600
[Guest]: cautionary tale, actually. And, you know, Tawaif narratives are bound with cautionary

01:17:26.600 --> 01:17:33.240
[Guest]: tales. So she loses her way because of her own hubris. And then ultimately, because she

01:17:33.240 --> 01:17:39.920
[Guest]: had for long served, you know, the raag and raagni as well. It's they who come to her

01:17:39.920 --> 01:17:46.120
[Guest]: rescue literally. And she finds herself in a forest, and they rescue her. And they take

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:52.480
[Guest]: her away. I mean, it's an incredible story. So, and it speaks to me about the intensely

01:17:52.480 --> 01:17:57.880
[Guest]: closed relationship that, you know, these musicians have with their music. That's actually

01:17:57.880 --> 01:18:05.720
[Guest]: what it's speaking about. In a very personal relationship, which is defining so much of

01:18:05.720 --> 01:18:09.720
[Guest]: their being that ultimately, where you're saying that if I'm in the danger of being

01:18:09.720 --> 01:18:13.960
[Guest]: killed, it is my music which will come and save me. And music literally in the shape

01:18:13.960 --> 01:18:21.280
[Guest]: of a man or woman personified. I just found that those stories fascinating.

01:18:21.280 --> 01:18:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And less listeners think that the book is just a magic realist exercise. It's not just

01:18:25.600 --> 01:18:30.920
[Amit Varma]: a small part of it. I found a lot of the background research very meticulous. And I am kind of

01:18:30.920 --> 01:18:37.320
[Amit Varma]: fairly familiar with that period. What I, you know, found very interesting and wasn't

01:18:37.320 --> 01:18:43.560
[Amit Varma]: so clued into was one you've written, of course, about slavery, that it was so prevalent, and

01:18:43.560 --> 01:18:46.920
[Amit Varma]: it's not something that happened in America in the mid 19th century and was abolished.

01:18:46.920 --> 01:18:50.840
[Amit Varma]: It was very prevalent in India, where people would sell their children and people would

01:18:50.840 --> 01:18:57.560
[Amit Varma]: even sell their wives and all of that. There'd be sales deeds. They'll be sales deeds.

01:18:57.560 --> 01:19:04.480
[Amit Varma]: Shockingly enough. Yeah. So it is part of our recent history as well. And what our culture,

01:19:04.480 --> 01:19:12.000
[Amit Varma]: our culture, as it were. And what also kind of struck me was how much of the wife families,

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:17.040
[Amit Varma]: how much of the community is sustained through adoption. Like Dharman BB's aunt was herself

01:19:17.040 --> 01:19:23.320
[Amit Varma]: adopted, as you pointed out. And there's a lot of sort of, like you write, quote, adoption

01:19:23.320 --> 01:19:28.320
[Amit Varma]: of girl children among childless Tawaifs was most common, but it was not considered unusual

01:19:28.320 --> 01:19:32.680
[Amit Varma]: for Tawaifs with biological daughters of their own to adopt as well. More daughters in the

01:19:32.680 --> 01:19:38.100
[Amit Varma]: family meant more earning members and prosperity for the quota. Stop quote, sort of pointing

01:19:38.100 --> 01:19:42.840
[Guest]: to the economic incentives of all of this. No, but actually, as the book points out in

01:19:42.840 --> 01:19:49.040
[Guest]: the later chapters, and that is from post 1857, you know, the rule shifted from East

01:19:49.040 --> 01:19:58.040
[Guest]: India Company to the crown, the British crown directly. And so, you know, there's the IPC

01:19:58.040 --> 01:20:06.520
[Guest]: and all of these, the law changed. And adoption by Tawaifs was declared illegal. So, you know,

01:20:06.520 --> 01:20:11.880
[Guest]: those Tawaifs who had already adopted, well, then their foster daughters could not claim

01:20:11.880 --> 01:20:17.240
[Guest]: property because it was not recognized by the state. And any adoption done thereafter

01:20:17.240 --> 01:20:25.480
[Guest]: from 1860 onwards, was anyway deemed illegal and a criminal activity. So, and then there's

01:20:25.480 --> 01:20:34.080
[Guest]: this entire thing about how this family, Sadabahar and her, you know, twin, and their foster

01:20:34.080 --> 01:20:42.600
[Guest]: mothers lose their entire fortune in being taken to the courts over this whole issue.

01:20:42.600 --> 01:20:49.720
[Guest]: But the thing is that adoption was fairly common. And there are hangovers of some of

01:20:49.720 --> 01:20:56.600
[Guest]: those terms which still remain. So, you know, for instance, even to this day, I was rather

01:20:56.600 --> 01:21:03.080
[Guest]: shocked when they use the term Malkin. Malkin is kind of slave owner, I mean, kind of conjures

01:21:03.080 --> 01:21:11.560
[Guest]: up things. So, but it's obviously a hangover because Malkins, now they say it simply means,

01:21:11.560 --> 01:21:18.080
[Guest]: you know, like the mother of an active, this is being now used in the context of bar dancers,

01:21:18.080 --> 01:21:25.520
[Guest]: some of whom come from Tawaif families. But the process of adoption from the outside stopped.

01:21:25.520 --> 01:21:31.800
[Guest]: And that is because by the criminalization of the entire tradition by the colonial state.

01:21:31.800 --> 01:21:38.520
[Guest]: So, A, they were being, you know, this point of time, 1870s, 1880s, you have a plethora

01:21:38.520 --> 01:21:46.960
[Guest]: of court cases, if one comes across in the archives. And where especially actually of,

01:21:46.960 --> 01:21:54.120
[Guest]: you know, dancers and singer communities from West India and also from the Devdasi communities,

01:21:54.120 --> 01:22:00.560
[Guest]: and also Tawaif, some Tawaifs, which is on litigation, which is on this very fact, that

01:22:00.560 --> 01:22:07.040
[Guest]: oh, so and so is, you know, an adopted daughter, well, her claims upon property being contested,

01:22:07.040 --> 01:22:13.080
[Guest]: because she's illegal. So, you know, that, so, de facto, then her claims are not recognized.

01:22:13.080 --> 01:22:18.080
[Guest]: So, this process, there was an entire, there seems to have been a big churning, actually,

01:22:18.080 --> 01:22:23.520
[Guest]: within the community. That's actually where my archival research came in handy, is looking

01:22:23.520 --> 01:22:34.320
[Guest]: at that and piecing the things. Also, I think that somewhere around late 19th, early 20th

01:22:34.320 --> 01:22:40.160
[Guest]: century, at least from within the Tawaif communities, adoption from the outside came to an end,

01:22:40.160 --> 01:22:48.880
[Guest]: because there is no memory of adopting daughters from the outside. Yes, adopting your own nieces,

01:22:48.880 --> 01:22:54.360
[Guest]: that kind of within the family, that continued. And that continued, because, well, you know,

01:22:54.360 --> 01:22:59.320
[Guest]: they just felt that that needed no official sanction. One of the smart things that Tawaif

01:22:59.320 --> 01:23:03.900
[Guest]: communities in the North did, which I don't know why it was not followed by the communities

01:23:03.900 --> 01:23:10.880
[Guest]: of dancers and singers in the West and South, was that they actually had an embargo of not

01:23:10.880 --> 01:23:19.800
[Guest]: accessing law courts. It's really very interesting. And because they kind of realized quite early

01:23:19.800 --> 01:23:26.200
[Guest]: on that, look, we are the losers every time we drag some family matter or, you know, issue

01:23:26.200 --> 01:23:33.120
[Guest]: into the courts, because there's just so much bias and hostility and prejudice against well,

01:23:33.120 --> 01:23:38.920
[Guest]: so called prostitutes. So, who are not and certainly their customary lifestyle, their

01:23:38.920 --> 01:23:44.120
[Guest]: norms, customs are not being recognized at all. So, there was a certain embargo, which

01:23:44.120 --> 01:23:50.040
[Guest]: is really very interesting, that they imposed, you know, if you go to access, if any family

01:23:50.040 --> 01:23:56.840
[Guest]: does do that, then they would be excommunicated. Now, whether that was imposed all across all

01:23:56.840 --> 01:24:01.760
[Guest]: the communities in the North, I don't know. But it seems to have been imposed, at least

01:24:01.760 --> 01:24:06.640
[Guest]: in a lot of places. And people have a memory of that. And in a sense, it's a fantastic

01:24:06.640 --> 01:24:12.760
[Amit Varma]: as an example of fighting colonialism, you know, which would our nationalists today would

01:24:12.760 --> 01:24:17.560
[Amit Varma]: perhaps not think of that as a typical example. But it's an act of civil disobedience. Yeah.

01:24:17.560 --> 01:24:23.120
[Guest]: So they basically here it was a survival of protecting your own customs and norms. And

01:24:23.120 --> 01:24:34.400
[Guest]: very typically, the answer I would get was, we don't meddle in your affairs, you don't

01:24:34.400 --> 01:24:39.640
[Guest]: meddle in ours. So, we don't want to go to the courts, we'll settle our affairs ourselves,

01:24:39.640 --> 01:24:45.960
[Guest]: because they realize they're very smart, that they were losers in colonial courts. And that,

01:24:45.960 --> 01:24:52.200
[Guest]: you know, kind of discomfort of accessing law courts, kind of still continues. I mean,

01:24:52.200 --> 01:24:58.560
[Guest]: it's not although now, of course, there are no tawaifs. So, you know, this, but, and things

01:24:58.560 --> 01:25:06.120
[Guest]: have changed substantially. But you hear of fewer numbers of cases going to the courts,

01:25:06.120 --> 01:25:09.960
[Guest]: the emphasis still is of resolving it within the community somehow.

01:25:09.960 --> 01:25:17.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the most striking factoids, which provided an impetus to the already moralistic

01:25:17.920 --> 01:25:24.640
[Amit Varma]: stance of the British, the most striking factoid was that more soldiers died in the 1857 mutiny

01:25:24.640 --> 01:25:29.120
[Amit Varma]: from venereal disease than in combat. And this completely blew my mind more European

01:25:29.120 --> 01:25:34.560
[Amit Varma]: soldiers died in 1857 from venereal disease than in combat. And, you know, you already

01:25:34.560 --> 01:25:41.140
[Amit Varma]: had existing offenses of adultery and enticement in the Indian Penal Code. To that it was added,

01:25:41.140 --> 01:25:45.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, prostitutes and dancing girls, quote, unquote, as you've said, were forbidden from

01:25:45.100 --> 01:25:49.440
[Amit Varma]: adopting children, since this was presumed to be for the purpose of inducting them into

01:25:49.440 --> 01:25:55.960
[Amit Varma]: prostitution, your words, and you also say, quote, colonial lawmaking, thus contributed

01:25:55.960 --> 01:26:01.120
[Amit Varma]: substantially to the dissolution of the autonomy and privileged position as independent women

01:26:01.120 --> 01:26:07.000
[Amit Varma]: of substance that courtesans had customarily enjoyed, stop quote, and then you talk about

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:11.360
[Amit Varma]: how you know, state surveillance goes up and there are all these efforts.

01:26:11.360 --> 01:26:17.080
[Guest]: That is one part of it. That is the criminal aspect of criminalizing the tradition. The

01:26:17.080 --> 01:26:22.640
[Guest]: other aspect was in terms of even in terms of personal, you know, the so called, you

01:26:22.640 --> 01:26:29.920
[Guest]: know, this, the lawmaking was divided into, you know, this criminal and personal. Yeah.

01:26:29.920 --> 01:26:39.840
[Guest]: So and so here, what happened was that I mean, that had existed even pre 1857. But post 1857,

01:26:39.840 --> 01:26:47.360
[Guest]: you had Muslim personal law, Hindu personal law. So communities were to be governed, you

01:26:47.360 --> 01:26:54.160
[Guest]: know, their matters pertaining to inheritance, separation, property, all the civil matters

01:26:54.160 --> 01:27:00.480
[Guest]: would be and that was to placate actually, you know, what was perceived to be the traditional,

01:27:00.480 --> 01:27:07.640
[Guest]: more traditional elements within Indian society, who it was felt had got very offended by,

01:27:07.640 --> 01:27:14.840
[Guest]: you know, colonial evangelical activity. And that was one of the reasons for 1857. Now,

01:27:14.840 --> 01:27:22.520
[Guest]: so all civil matters came under these, you know, Hindu law, Muslim law, Christian law,

01:27:22.520 --> 01:27:29.520
[Guest]: etc, etc. These were necessarily, you know, they are necessarily patriarchal in nature,

01:27:29.520 --> 01:27:36.000
[Guest]: because where men are privileged in all of these, after all, over women, any of these

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:44.000
[Guest]: law things. So the customs, you know, whereas what the Tawaifs or any of the communities,

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:49.600
[Guest]: it's not just the Tawaifs, I mean, it's any of the communities, the other communities,

01:27:49.600 --> 01:27:56.400
[Guest]: they had followed thus far customary law. Now, customary law a because they were all

01:27:56.400 --> 01:28:01.800
[Guest]: these communities who are not of, you know, so called high caste, you know, many of them

01:28:01.800 --> 01:28:08.240
[Guest]: did not have all of this written down. This came as part of a certain oral, you know,

01:28:08.240 --> 01:28:16.040
[Guest]: tradition, and oral memory of law making that what happens is, and it does not fall neatly

01:28:16.040 --> 01:28:22.880
[Guest]: into being Hindu or Muslim. So for instance, Nat Tawaifs, if they are Nat, Hindu Nat Tawaifs

01:28:22.880 --> 01:28:28.400
[Guest]: and Muslim Nat Tawaifs, they all follow the same, you know, customs. And that is true

01:28:28.400 --> 01:28:33.920
[Guest]: for all the other communities of Tawaifs also, in terms of inheritance, property, whatever,

01:28:33.920 --> 01:28:39.480
[Guest]: whatever. Now, as far as the, and where, of course, women are being privileged, you know,

01:28:39.480 --> 01:28:45.760
[Guest]: in the Tawaifs. Now, if they go to the, this was the greatest blow to the position and

01:28:45.760 --> 01:28:50.840
[Guest]: autonomy of the Tawaifs, you know, and one of the reasons why they stopped accessing

01:28:50.840 --> 01:28:55.840
[Guest]: law courts, because when they went to the law court, the first thing was that, you know,

01:28:55.840 --> 01:29:03.040
[Guest]: if there was any case, you know, say a brother contesting against his sister, the brother

01:29:03.040 --> 01:29:08.600
[Guest]: automatically stood much greater chance of winning the case, because that is how actually,

01:29:08.600 --> 01:29:14.280
[Guest]: whether it is, you know, Muslim personal law or Hindu personal law, it is patriarchal,

01:29:14.280 --> 01:29:21.640
[Guest]: it privileges men, any of these law makings. Secondly, their customary law was not recognized

01:29:21.640 --> 01:29:26.240
[Guest]: because they said you are prostitutes, you are criminals. So to claim that you are, this

01:29:26.240 --> 01:29:31.880
[Guest]: is custom is to say as if a band of thieves has a certain customs. So, you know, their

01:29:31.880 --> 01:29:37.240
[Guest]: customs were disparaged. And then thirdly, there's a certain identity of being either

01:29:37.240 --> 01:29:42.560
[Guest]: Hindu or Muslim imposed on them. It's fascinating. If you go through the legal archives, where

01:29:42.560 --> 01:29:48.160
[Guest]: actually there are these contests made saying, you know, but your honour, my client is neither

01:29:48.160 --> 01:29:53.880
[Guest]: Hindu nor Muslim, but identifies herself as what, what, what, and this is no how can that

01:29:53.880 --> 01:30:00.440
[Guest]: be? It's very clear. Her name is this, her mother's name was this, they follow the custom

01:30:00.440 --> 01:30:06.240
[Guest]: of burial. And so they have to be, you know, Muslim. So that there's a certain imposition

01:30:06.240 --> 01:30:12.600
[Guest]: is also a certain ways in which there's a congealing of identities that takes place

01:30:12.600 --> 01:30:18.440
[Guest]: in late 19th century. It's all a parcel of ways in which identities is this disparate

01:30:18.440 --> 01:30:25.880
[Guest]: Hindu, Muslim, they get shaped also in this period. But actually, it's also it's a greatly

01:30:25.880 --> 01:30:31.960
[Guest]: contributed to the erosion of the status of the wives. So it is not just the criminalization,

01:30:31.960 --> 01:30:37.120
[Guest]: which is, you know, in terms of state surveillance, in terms of, you know, like, for instance,

01:30:37.120 --> 01:30:42.440
[Guest]: the ways in which the contagious disease acts, where you were had to go and get yourself

01:30:42.440 --> 01:30:48.840
[Guest]: compulsorily, I mean, you examined, etc, etc. All that was there anyway. It was at least

01:30:48.840 --> 01:30:55.080
[Guest]: civil law, which was really, really eroded their position, which is why actually, they

01:30:55.080 --> 01:30:59.840
[Guest]: said goodbye, they had a good sense to say goodbye to the law courts, as far as these

01:30:59.840 --> 01:31:02.360
[Guest]: cases were concerned, they resolved it within themselves.

01:31:02.360 --> 01:31:09.720
[Amit Varma]: No, it also strikes me about how it is such a blow to the beautiful diversity of our country

01:31:09.720 --> 01:31:15.320
[Amit Varma]: by, you know, using the coercive power of the state to force them into these categories.

01:31:15.320 --> 01:31:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And even any kind of passive resistance that they do, like, you know, boycotting the courts

01:31:19.280 --> 01:31:23.560
[Amit Varma]: will eventually fail, because we are talking about them in the past tense. We you know,

01:31:23.560 --> 01:31:26.520
[Amit Varma]: we and like this, I'm sure we've destroyed so many other

01:31:26.520 --> 01:31:32.240
[Guest]: No, also, these are communities which were always much more marginal, you know, yeah.

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:38.440
[Guest]: I mean, they were dependent upon their survival on patronage. The fact is that their patrons

01:31:38.440 --> 01:31:44.600
[Guest]: themselves were, you know, in many ways, negotiating, I mean, either they were buying their piece,

01:31:44.600 --> 01:31:49.600
[Guest]: and that was fine with the colonial state, but many of them were not able to buy that

01:31:49.600 --> 01:31:55.120
[Guest]: piece also. And these are communities that are anyway, much more marginal, much more

01:31:55.120 --> 01:32:00.520
[Guest]: vulnerable to all the pulls and pushes. And it's not just the Tawafs, you have communities

01:32:00.520 --> 01:32:08.200
[Guest]: across board, who were being pushed around in this ways and being forced to then start,

01:32:08.200 --> 01:32:13.960
[Guest]: you know, self identifying themselves in certain ways, which, which, you know, and I think

01:32:13.960 --> 01:32:21.560
[Guest]: that had a very profound impact in terms of the reshaping of Indian society, very, very

01:32:21.560 --> 01:32:26.240
[Guest]: profound ways. And I think that really needs more study and more work.

01:32:26.240 --> 01:32:29.160
[Amit Varma]: And you've of course, written very beautifully in your book about how through the second

01:32:29.160 --> 01:32:33.000
[Amit Varma]: half of the 19th century, they are more and more already being marginal, they're more

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:39.240
[Amit Varma]: and more marginalized, and so on. And interestingly, they have that brief moment in the mainstream,

01:32:39.240 --> 01:32:43.520
[Amit Varma]: when the gramophone comes in. And it's almost they who make the gramophone mainstream instead

01:32:43.520 --> 01:32:47.560
[Amit Varma]: of the other way around. Tell me a bit about that phase and how that played out.

01:32:47.560 --> 01:32:53.080
[Guest]: Well, you know, the coming of the gramophone, I mean, that's there in the book, it's actually

01:32:53.080 --> 01:32:59.040
[Guest]: all well documented, you know, this, there was a big market with the coming of the actual

01:32:59.040 --> 01:33:06.440
[Guest]: gramophone and the recording machines. There's this whole like, big fascination for the recorded

01:33:06.440 --> 01:33:12.040
[Guest]: voice. So one part, of course, was to record your own voice, your loved ones, etc, etc.

01:33:12.040 --> 01:33:18.960
[Guest]: But there was much greater demand for music, indigenous music. That's how it's very fascinating

01:33:18.960 --> 01:33:24.440
[Guest]: that early 20th century, you have these all these companies from Europe and America, you

01:33:24.440 --> 01:33:30.720
[Guest]: know, just racing and coming to India, who's going to beat, be the first one to reach here,

01:33:30.720 --> 01:33:37.280
[Guest]: because this was recognized as a huge market, the huge potential. Now, what is really interesting

01:33:37.280 --> 01:33:43.880
[Guest]: is that, okay, they come in. And the people, the only class of musicians who really show

01:33:43.880 --> 01:33:52.960
[Guest]: an interest in recording for them, are the Tawaifs and the Devdasis. And very few of

01:33:52.960 --> 01:33:59.160
[Guest]: the male musicians, especially, you know, the Khayal singers and Drupad Diyas and all,

01:33:59.160 --> 01:34:06.160
[Guest]: you have much fewer numbers. Why is that? Well, many reasons. See, why the men didn't

01:34:06.160 --> 01:34:13.080
[Guest]: want it is, you know, the obvious reason is a, the purest amongst them felt that it compromised

01:34:13.080 --> 01:34:17.920
[Guest]: the integrity of their music. Because something, you know, Khayal can be sung over so many

01:34:17.920 --> 01:34:25.480
[Guest]: hours, it has to be like, you have to explore leisurely each nuance of the raag and then

01:34:25.480 --> 01:34:31.200
[Guest]: you hear this was even less than, you know, three minutes, you have to get it over with.

01:34:31.200 --> 01:34:38.480
[Guest]: So obviously, there was, the purest felt offended, it was seen as something terribly crass and

01:34:38.480 --> 01:34:43.560
[Guest]: crude. Commercialization, yeah, I mean, so that was

01:34:43.560 --> 01:34:51.440
[Guest]: happening and a certain vulgarity. So that was one part of it. But well, I mean, all,

01:34:51.440 --> 01:34:55.640
[Guest]: you know, all the, this is very, all very high minded. But actually, there were also

01:34:55.640 --> 01:35:02.480
[Guest]: other reasons for it, which were less high minded, which was a, you know, the value of

01:35:02.480 --> 01:35:09.360
[Guest]: music of some of the effect was based on the fact of its exclusive worth, so that it was

01:35:09.360 --> 01:35:15.560
[Guest]: being performed for a small audience in these exclusive gatherings of, you know, in the

01:35:15.560 --> 01:35:21.680
[Guest]: courts and in princely mayfields. And so, they felt that that their value, the value

01:35:21.680 --> 01:35:27.200
[Guest]: of the music would go, if it was accessible to all on the gramophone, and could be easily

01:35:27.200 --> 01:35:33.080
[Guest]: copied by everyone. So then what is their exclusive value of their music or their style?

01:35:33.080 --> 01:35:39.720
[Guest]: And style could be copied by everyone then. There was a genuine real fear of plagiarism.

01:35:39.720 --> 01:35:47.120
[Guest]: So which dates back then till at that time. And, and the third was actually, you know,

01:35:47.120 --> 01:35:52.440
[Guest]: and you hear that is in terms of, you know, the horn, the gramophone horn, which there

01:35:52.440 --> 01:35:58.760
[Guest]: was a fear that this actually, I mean, it's actually speaks of many things, if you think

01:35:58.760 --> 01:36:04.360
[Guest]: about it, there was this thing, fear that this sucks the soul of the very singer of

01:36:04.360 --> 01:36:10.520
[Guest]: the singer. People have similar fears about cameras and their photos being taken. Yeah.

01:36:10.520 --> 01:36:18.440
[Guest]: So and well, I mean, you know, if you were to look deeper into that, it's this, you know,

01:36:18.440 --> 01:36:23.800
[Guest]: in terms of looking at the market and music and what it meant, etc, etc, then that can

01:36:23.800 --> 01:36:31.400
[Guest]: one can go into that. So the male musicians had those fears, real fears. And therefore

01:36:31.400 --> 01:36:38.240
[Guest]: very few of them till at least almost 1920s. Very few of them much fewer numbers except

01:36:38.240 --> 01:36:45.880
[Guest]: for certain notable, you know, examples like Ustad Abdul Kareem Khan Sahib, he sang, but

01:36:45.880 --> 01:36:52.680
[Guest]: otherwise you have very few people. The wives who came in, you know, large numbers, they

01:36:52.680 --> 01:36:58.200
[Guest]: were the main people who recorded for the gramophone, the wives and the devdasis. See,

01:36:58.200 --> 01:37:03.280
[Guest]: they were being hounded out of the kothas. There was an entire, you know, this period

01:37:03.280 --> 01:37:09.000
[Guest]: coincided with this whole anti-notch movement where, you know, there was this entire public

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:17.440
[Guest]: campaign against organizing notches, as they were called, natch, you know, the wives' performances

01:37:17.440 --> 01:37:25.360
[Guest]: in elite homes, you know, for weddings or other celebrations. So there's an entire hounding

01:37:25.360 --> 01:37:31.800
[Guest]: that was going on in various ways in the press, in railways, where, you know, the patrons

01:37:31.800 --> 01:37:37.640
[Guest]: would be stopped physically from holding these notches, etc. So they were under pressure

01:37:37.640 --> 01:37:45.200
[Guest]: to reinvent themselves. And the gramophone came along and was almost perfect for many

01:37:45.200 --> 01:37:51.920
[Guest]: of them to actually reinvent themselves as gramophone singers. And to, you know, to make

01:37:51.920 --> 01:37:56.600
[Amit Varma]: an image, have an image makeover. So on the one hand, you already have that artistic training

01:37:56.600 --> 01:38:00.440
[Amit Varma]: in your, you know, great performers. And on the other hand, if you ain't got nothing,

01:38:00.440 --> 01:38:05.160
[Guest]: you got nothing to lose. So you just kind of go with it. And so I think also with tawaifs,

01:38:05.160 --> 01:38:12.040
[Guest]: if you read their biographies, then you realize that these are women who are always at the

01:38:12.040 --> 01:38:18.840
[Guest]: forefront of exploring, you know, these long frontiers. Yeah. So I mean, also, you know,

01:38:18.840 --> 01:38:24.360
[Guest]: that great travelers, I mean, forget about being great at every level. I mean, you know,

01:38:24.360 --> 01:38:29.560
[Guest]: they were always willing that if there's an opportunity, which they could, there was a

01:38:29.560 --> 01:38:35.520
[Guest]: possibility of some opportunity to pick up everything and to strike new roots at a completely

01:38:35.520 --> 01:38:42.160
[Guest]: new place. It speaks of a certain way of being. I mean, and that's, of course, you know, a

01:38:42.160 --> 01:38:48.640
[Guest]: community living by their wits, also of survivors. And so they're constantly moving. I think

01:38:48.640 --> 01:38:53.680
[Guest]: moving physically from one place to another, but also then that also translates in being

01:38:53.680 --> 01:38:59.880
[Guest]: able to move from one kind of a performance space to another kind of a performance space.

01:38:59.880 --> 01:39:06.720
[Guest]: You know, being open to new opportunities in life. I think so it was not just the gramophone,

01:39:06.720 --> 01:39:12.320
[Guest]: they were theater, then there were films. So in fact, in terms of the ways in which

01:39:12.320 --> 01:39:20.440
[Guest]: we see now, I mean, the cinema and theater and the recording industry, recording music,

01:39:20.440 --> 01:39:23.280
[Guest]: it was so much to tawaifs.

01:39:23.280 --> 01:39:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And would you say the community really died out? Or would you say it just got absorbed

01:39:26.520 --> 01:39:30.640
[Amit Varma]: into the mainstream just as the arts got absorbed into the mainstream in the sense that now

01:39:30.640 --> 01:39:34.440
[Amit Varma]: there is no taboo against, you know, people will send their daughters to learn Bharatnatyam

01:39:34.440 --> 01:39:39.960
[Amit Varma]: and Kathak and there's no taboo. In fact, there's even an aspirational sort of attraction

01:39:39.960 --> 01:39:42.960
[Amit Varma]: for the arts and, you know, all of that.

01:39:42.960 --> 01:39:48.080
[Guest]: So the community died out, not just because it did, unfortunately, it would have been,

01:39:48.080 --> 01:39:55.880
[Guest]: I think, you know, there are ways in which, sad as it may be, but ways in which certain,

01:39:55.880 --> 01:40:01.120
[Guest]: you know, art forms, etc, have been wiped out, you know, in terms of, well, them not

01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:08.440
[Guest]: being as popular or the television, you know, hegemonic kind of entertainments, market driven

01:40:08.440 --> 01:40:09.440
[Guest]: entertainments taking over.

01:40:09.440 --> 01:40:11.760
[Amit Varma]: Where everything is dumbed down and all that, yeah.

01:40:11.760 --> 01:40:16.840
[Guest]: But this is not, I don't think that is the case here. I mean, that just played one part

01:40:16.840 --> 01:40:24.240
[Guest]: of it. The major part of it was the stigmatizing and sustained stigmatizing and shaming of

01:40:24.240 --> 01:40:29.960
[Guest]: this community, where they were literally hounded and pushed out of the kothas.

01:40:29.960 --> 01:40:33.560
[Amit Varma]: To the extent that you pointed out that many former Tawaifs won't even call themselves

01:40:33.560 --> 01:40:36.760
[Guest]: dad, they'll say they're Gaikas or they're Singhas or whatever.

01:40:36.760 --> 01:40:42.840
[Guest]: There's no hope in hell that you will find one former Tawaif who will acknowledge, you

01:40:42.840 --> 01:40:48.400
[Guest]: know, call herself a Tawaif to a stranger. There's no way, because Tawaif now anyway

01:40:48.400 --> 01:40:54.920
[Guest]: is synonymous with being a sex worker. We may argue, and rightly so, that why should

01:40:54.920 --> 01:41:02.200
[Guest]: a sex worker be looked down upon? But that is how society does, you know, look upon them.

01:41:02.200 --> 01:41:10.000
[Guest]: And it's also, it's actually a certain systematic vilification that they have suffered, you

01:41:10.000 --> 01:41:16.280
[Guest]: know, over the decades, till actually, say in Banaras, you know, that hounding, physical

01:41:16.280 --> 01:41:25.600
[Guest]: hounding went on till they were forced to shut kothas, finally, by the early 1980s.

01:41:25.600 --> 01:41:30.280
[Guest]: And that just didn't happen because, oh, people's taste changed. That too happened. See, a lot

01:41:30.280 --> 01:41:35.640
[Guest]: of things happened together. For instance, one thing that happened was that, you know,

01:41:35.640 --> 01:41:42.000
[Guest]: the emphasis on companion marriages. So, you know, with the emphasis on women's education,

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:47.720
[Guest]: women coming out of parda, getting educated, the emphasis on marriages where your husband

01:41:47.720 --> 01:41:54.240
[Guest]: and wife share, are friends, share ideas. That's a completely new concept for India

01:41:54.240 --> 01:42:00.800
[Guest]: in many ways. So, if the emphasis on that kind of a relationship, then really, I mean,

01:42:00.800 --> 01:42:06.720
[Guest]: the need for a mistress who is educated, if your wife is educated, you know, those, that

01:42:06.720 --> 01:42:13.880
[Guest]: itself, kind of was, you know, that need lessens. Even that need for companionship, apart from

01:42:13.880 --> 01:42:22.200
[Guest]: sex. Of a cultivated, you know, companion. I mean, if that kind of, you know, was being

01:42:22.200 --> 01:42:27.880
[Guest]: undercut and cut away. But in terms of the cinema itself, the coming up of cinema and

01:42:27.880 --> 01:42:34.280
[Guest]: film music, that I think went and before that, the gramophone, recorded music. The thing

01:42:34.280 --> 01:42:38.720
[Guest]: about, because otherwise, kothas were also a site, was not just a sexual site. Exactly.

01:42:38.720 --> 01:42:44.680
[Guest]: It was a site for going to listen to music. But if there was recorded music by the same

01:42:44.680 --> 01:42:50.280
[Guest]: voices available, then, you know, kotha was not the only place you could access music.

01:42:50.280 --> 01:42:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And not just that, that also struck me that, you know, when you mentioned kotha shutting

01:42:53.080 --> 01:42:58.040
[Amit Varma]: down earlier, it struck me that many of us may attach the same stigma to kothas as in

01:42:58.040 --> 01:43:04.320
[Amit Varma]: note or rebrothels, as we do to tawaifs. But as your book brings out, they were both kala

01:43:04.320 --> 01:43:08.520
[Amit Varma]: academies of a sort. They were places where people interested in the arts and the culture

01:43:08.520 --> 01:43:13.760
[Amit Varma]: would gather. An early form of the literary festival, in fact, where, you know, you speak

01:43:13.760 --> 01:43:18.000
[Amit Varma]: of kothas, where you have these platforms and you have places for people to say it.

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:23.480
[Guest]: And this is where all of art is sort of centered. All these discussions, you know, literary

01:43:23.480 --> 01:43:28.720
[Guest]: discussions with the tawaif playing hostess. So you have all these poets and they're, you

01:43:28.720 --> 01:43:36.560
[Guest]: know, they're reciting. And so kotha was actually a literary site for a whole lot of literary

01:43:36.560 --> 01:43:41.760
[Guest]: cultural activity. Exactly. We can note it now in a singular way as just being a site

01:43:41.760 --> 01:43:45.240
[Guest]: for sexual activity. That was not necessarily so.

01:43:45.240 --> 01:43:49.600
[Amit Varma]: So we've spoken for almost two hours about your book and I'd recommend all my listeners

01:43:49.600 --> 01:43:54.240
[Amit Varma]: read it because it is both entertaining and moving and enlightening. I think it carries

01:43:54.240 --> 01:43:59.040
[Amit Varma]: so many insights about our society, which, you know, we tend to take so much for granted.

01:43:59.040 --> 01:44:05.040
[Amit Varma]: I'd like to now sort of turn to your working processes, you know, both across filmmaking

01:44:05.040 --> 01:44:11.480
[Amit Varma]: and writing and to writing itself. And one of those here is that, you know, you're working.

01:44:11.480 --> 01:44:14.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, these are people you're spending a lot of time with. They are your friends. They

01:44:14.920 --> 01:44:18.840
[Amit Varma]: are close to you. There is an intimacy there. You know, you point out about how, you know,

01:44:18.840 --> 01:44:23.960
[Amit Varma]: you got fever and your friend looked after you and all of that. But at the same time,

01:44:23.960 --> 01:44:28.440
[Amit Varma]: they are fulfilling a utilitarian role for you. You know, they are the means to the end

01:44:28.440 --> 01:44:32.840
[Amit Varma]: of your book, so to say. How do you sort of, you know, reconcile those things? Is that

01:44:32.840 --> 01:44:37.240
[Amit Varma]: something that sort of bothered you while writing the film or while writing the books?

01:44:37.240 --> 01:44:42.720
[Guest]: I don't think they would. I would call it utilitarian because the ways in which relationships

01:44:42.720 --> 01:44:49.360
[Guest]: flower and these are relationships that have flowered over a period of 20 years. You see,

01:44:49.360 --> 01:44:59.240
[Guest]: I started work on The Other Song way back, nearly 20 years, in 2001. And I finished the

01:44:59.240 --> 01:45:04.440
[Guest]: film along with the other two films, which is part of the trilogy. The trilogy got over

01:45:04.440 --> 01:45:10.880
[Guest]: in 2009. And then I started working on the book, which was a continuation, you know,

01:45:10.880 --> 01:45:17.920
[Guest]: with the same people and just the research, going deeper into the research. Both as a

01:45:17.920 --> 01:45:24.520
[Guest]: filmmaker, actually, I identify myself primarily as a filmmaker. You know, I mean, even now

01:45:24.520 --> 01:45:30.360
[Guest]: when people ask me as a filmmaker, the writer bit is very new to me. And well, as a writer

01:45:30.360 --> 01:45:40.160
[Guest]: now, my relationship with all the people that I've worked with, if one has a utilitarian

01:45:40.160 --> 01:45:48.200
[Guest]: approach to, you know, people, there's only that far you go with people. If one is using

01:45:48.200 --> 01:45:57.000
[Guest]: them as a means to an end, then that remains just that. Then the kind of rich relationship

01:45:57.000 --> 01:46:02.960
[Guest]: between people as human beings, then you don't see them, you stop seeing them as human beings,

01:46:02.960 --> 01:46:08.120
[Guest]: because they just become a means to an end to you want your film done. So they are that.

01:46:08.120 --> 01:46:15.760
[Guest]: And in so many ways, then you're stripping them of their humanity. That's a real problem.

01:46:15.760 --> 01:46:25.440
[Guest]: So no, I do not see my relationships with everyone I work with are not, you know,

01:46:25.440 --> 01:46:29.080
[Amit Varma]: What I was sort of asking is that they're both personal, obviously, and genuine, but

01:46:29.080 --> 01:46:30.920
[Guest]: at the same time, there is an element that

01:46:30.920 --> 01:46:36.520
[Guest]: Well, we are working, we are researching, I am looking at their lives. And it's not

01:46:36.520 --> 01:46:41.160
[Guest]: that I will share an equally close relationship with everyone I work with. That is true. I

01:46:41.160 --> 01:46:49.280
[Guest]: don't. And I think that also depends from people to people, circumstances, etc. I think

01:46:49.280 --> 01:46:55.760
[Guest]: for me, that's not just for the wives that I've worked with. It's equally true for all

01:46:55.760 --> 01:46:58.760
[Guest]: the other people I've worked with all the other films I've made.

01:46:58.760 --> 01:47:03.440
[Guest]: I mean, it's a cliched question that's asked of nonfiction in general, actually had, you

01:47:03.440 --> 01:47:10.400
[Guest]: know, these are relationships that I forge, not necessarily don't have to be become my

01:47:10.400 --> 01:47:17.200
[Guest]: bosom buddies. But the relationships that I forge, and I take care, and I think that

01:47:17.200 --> 01:47:24.000
[Guest]: is reflected then in the films is one in terms of mutual respect. And that is why I mean,

01:47:24.000 --> 01:47:28.440
[Guest]: people always tell me, what takes so long in your film, you know, my films take so long

01:47:28.440 --> 01:47:34.040
[Guest]: in making, not all, but some of them have taken immensely long. And because, for me,

01:47:34.040 --> 01:47:41.720
[Guest]: the process is very important. You go wrong in the process, then you don't have a film.

01:47:41.720 --> 01:47:48.040
[Guest]: And the process is not just glibly saying, Oh, what does mutual respect mean? Mutual

01:47:48.040 --> 01:47:55.160
[Guest]: respect really means actually a of respecting the other person respecting the boundaries

01:47:55.160 --> 01:48:01.280
[Guest]: that they are setting out for themselves, respecting those and not trying to be clever

01:48:01.280 --> 01:48:05.560
[Guest]: and hoping the boss one day or the other, I'm going to skip them because people are

01:48:05.560 --> 01:48:10.600
[Guest]: not stupid. If they have some boundaries, learn to respect them the way you have boundaries

01:48:10.600 --> 01:48:15.920
[Guest]: and you want them to be respected. And yes, over a period of time, if you know, there's

01:48:15.920 --> 01:48:22.840
[Guest]: a relationship that intensifies and you know, you they allow you in good for you, if not

01:48:22.840 --> 01:48:29.880
[Guest]: too bad. It's also means of opening up yourself, you know, because that is a relationship and

01:48:29.880 --> 01:48:36.280
[Guest]: that is a real problem. The unequal power dynamics, especially in filmmaking, where

01:48:36.280 --> 01:48:42.680
[Guest]: I'm right up here, I'm looking at my subject, I expect them like with a microscope, I expect

01:48:42.680 --> 01:48:49.560
[Guest]: them to open up their lives. But what about me? You know, and I don't work like that.

01:48:49.560 --> 01:48:55.120
[Guest]: There is a certain giving and taking in terms of like sharing my life of sharing the way

01:48:55.120 --> 01:49:02.440
[Guest]: I am as a person. And that is building up of certain relationships, not necessarily

01:49:02.440 --> 01:49:08.840
[Guest]: of like friendship, but in terms of just also as colleagues, but relationships which have

01:49:08.840 --> 01:49:13.120
[Guest]: to be based on a certain equality. And I guess also based on honesty, because you're very

01:49:13.120 --> 01:49:17.680
[Guest]: upfront about what you're there for and how much they give is up to them. Absolutely.

01:49:17.680 --> 01:49:23.400
[Guest]: And so for instance, I mean, there is a certain process that is involved. And it's true from

01:49:23.400 --> 01:49:29.280
[Guest]: the film I've made, is that, especially with, you know, the trilogy I made, because it was

01:49:29.280 --> 01:49:35.960
[Guest]: very sensitive. Here were women who were really sharing parts of their lives with me, which

01:49:35.960 --> 01:49:42.000
[Guest]: I felt very privileged that they trusted me enough to do that. But then there was a certain

01:49:42.000 --> 01:49:49.000
[Guest]: process we followed. We cut the film and then the rough cut had to be passed by them before

01:49:49.000 --> 01:49:54.840
[Guest]: and anything. If they said, no, this, you know, people say something and then they change

01:49:54.840 --> 01:49:58.920
[Guest]: their mind and say, no, I'm not comfortable. I said that, but I don't want that to come

01:49:58.920 --> 01:50:07.200
[Guest]: in. You've got to respect that. Because I genuinely believe in, you know, in all humility

01:50:07.200 --> 01:50:14.080
[Guest]: that a film or a book is not more important than a human being or a human life. So, you

01:50:14.080 --> 01:50:21.920
[Guest]: know, you can do this, no great film at the expense of someone's, well, peace of mind

01:50:21.920 --> 01:50:31.000
[Guest]: or whatever, you know, their existence. That's how I work. And that makes for a very slow

01:50:31.000 --> 01:50:38.760
[Guest]: moving process. But I think at the end of the day, at least I sleep easier. You know,

01:50:38.760 --> 01:50:45.040
[Guest]: the relationships I've shared thus far with everyone I've worked with, it's like I feel

01:50:45.040 --> 01:50:52.040
[Guest]: yeah, fine. Some people have become lifelong friends. I mean, like the protagonist of the

01:50:52.040 --> 01:50:59.160
[Guest]: book and her family. I mean, that family is now family to me and she's a very close friend

01:50:59.160 --> 01:51:05.840
[Guest]: and comes and stays with me and all of that. There are some others who might not be my

01:51:05.840 --> 01:51:11.880
[Guest]: close buddies. But yes, we stay in touch. There is, you know, festivals, etc. You wish

01:51:11.880 --> 01:51:19.000
[Guest]: each other or whatever. So just I think it's also I just feel that in some ways I'm very

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:25.160
[Amit Varma]: lucky and which is my life. Very wise words. Let's kind of move on to the other thing that

01:51:25.160 --> 01:51:29.680
[Amit Varma]: was very interesting to me is that, you know, you made all these films, as you said, you're

01:51:29.680 --> 01:51:34.080
[Amit Varma]: mainly a filmmaker, and then you wrote this book, how different was constructing the book

01:51:34.080 --> 01:51:38.960
[Amit Varma]: as opposed to the film? Like, what were your sort of writing practices? How would you discipline

01:51:38.960 --> 01:51:41.800
[Amit Varma]: yourself? What did you learn about the process when you got into it?

01:51:41.800 --> 01:51:48.280
[Guest]: You know, in some ways, some of the basics are not that different. Because filmmaking,

01:51:48.280 --> 01:51:56.320
[Guest]: except in spurts, when you're working with a crew when you're shooting, or when you are

01:51:56.320 --> 01:52:02.760
[Guest]: finally putting it together with an editor, it's essentially a very lonely exercise. You

01:52:02.760 --> 01:52:13.160
[Guest]: are on your own. And not lonely, but on your own, rather. So in that sense, working on

01:52:13.160 --> 01:52:19.400
[Guest]: the book, didn't feel that very different. I mean, the research process was the same.

01:52:19.400 --> 01:52:24.440
[Guest]: I didn't do anything different. I followed the same processes, just that it became much

01:52:24.440 --> 01:52:32.120
[Guest]: more intense. The process of like my archival research, obviously had to be much more thorough,

01:52:32.120 --> 01:52:38.360
[Guest]: intense and long drawn out, wider than I'd done for a film. I don't need to do that much

01:52:38.360 --> 01:52:46.160
[Guest]: for a film which is at the maximum 120 minutes long, which has many other elements too.

01:52:46.160 --> 01:52:54.040
[Guest]: I think my greatest challenge as a while writing, and certainly in the first part, first phase,

01:52:54.040 --> 01:53:02.240
[Guest]: first few years, I'd say, A was to find my voice. I mean, as a filmmaker, over the years,

01:53:02.240 --> 01:53:09.880
[Guest]: you know, in some way, you fall, you get up, whatever, by just doing and you learn, you

01:53:09.880 --> 01:53:15.880
[Guest]: get a sense of what is working, what is not working, you get a grammar, you learn and

01:53:15.880 --> 01:53:23.320
[Guest]: as a film student, there's some basic grammar of the medium that one learned. Here I had

01:53:23.320 --> 01:53:29.120
[Guest]: to learn the grammar myself, or well, hope that I'm getting it right.

01:53:29.120 --> 01:53:33.520
[Amit Varma]: And also improvise a bit because it seems to me a very unconventional grammar for a

01:53:33.520 --> 01:53:38.240
[Amit Varma]: typical Western novel, or typical Western book rather, because it's actually a second

01:53:38.240 --> 01:53:43.440
[Amit Varma]: person voice, but contained within that is it very shifts to third person because you

01:53:43.440 --> 01:53:46.480
[Amit Varma]: sort of take over the narrative of that second person who's telling you.

01:53:46.480 --> 01:53:51.520
[Guest]: That was difficult to begin with, because that was the other part. That was the other

01:53:51.520 --> 01:53:59.360
[Guest]: challenge. So one was, of course, like, is this reading well? Is this reading at all?

01:53:59.360 --> 01:54:04.480
[Guest]: Because as a filmmaker, when I see something, I say, okay, this shot is not working. And

01:54:04.480 --> 01:54:10.320
[Guest]: I know why this is not working. And I could have a sense of what could work, I might have

01:54:10.320 --> 01:54:17.800
[Guest]: not done it. But at least I have a sense, something else will. As a first time writer,

01:54:17.800 --> 01:54:22.680
[Guest]: that was a challenge. You know, I constantly like, like scared.

01:54:22.680 --> 01:54:27.080
[Amit Varma]: And this seemed to me to be a very bold choice is going with the second person account, second

01:54:27.080 --> 01:54:31.080
[Amit Varma]: person voice. And then, you know, though it's mostly third person, because it's that person's

01:54:31.080 --> 01:54:32.080
[Guest]: voice speaking.

01:54:32.080 --> 01:54:38.360
[Guest]: Well, this came out of the other challenge. And that challenge was, how do you write the

01:54:38.360 --> 01:54:45.720
[Guest]: story of people who are living, who are very much there, who do not wish to have their

01:54:45.720 --> 01:54:53.880
[Guest]: identities revealed, but whose story you wish to tell honestly, because it's very important

01:54:53.880 --> 01:55:01.960
[Guest]: to share those stories. It's really important. But how do you protect them, their identity

01:55:01.960 --> 01:55:08.960
[Guest]: in the process? That, I think, was my toughest challenge. Because it's much easier to write

01:55:08.960 --> 01:55:14.520
[Guest]: about people who are dead and gone, you know. But these are living families. And I have

01:55:14.520 --> 01:55:22.240
[Guest]: a sense of responsibility, duty towards them. You can't just, like, put them out, you know,

01:55:22.240 --> 01:55:30.440
[Guest]: to... So, okay, okay, I changed their names. But that was the simpler part. Changing names,

01:55:30.440 --> 01:55:37.500
[Guest]: then I tried, but that wasn't good enough. Because I was fearful, maybe not everyone,

01:55:37.500 --> 01:55:42.280
[Guest]: but at least some people who knew the, or knew of them, could still be able to figure

01:55:42.280 --> 01:55:49.440
[Guest]: out, this is so-and-so. Because there were certain things I wasn't changing. The Bhabhua

01:55:49.440 --> 01:55:55.240
[Guest]: was not changed, this town that they come from, originally come from, and Banaras. So

01:55:55.240 --> 01:55:58.840
[Guest]: I was very fearful that then people could perhaps...

01:55:58.840 --> 01:56:00.240
[Amit Varma]: Put the pieces together.

01:56:00.240 --> 01:56:07.320
[Guest]: Right, put the pieces. And I didn't want that. So then became this challenge that, okay,

01:56:07.320 --> 01:56:13.360
[Guest]: the thing is that my stories have to be authentic. And they have to be as they were told to,

01:56:13.360 --> 01:56:18.560
[Guest]: you know, they have to be narrated as they were told to me. But they don't necessarily

01:56:18.560 --> 01:56:26.280
[Guest]: have to be exactly of the same person. So once I decided that, you know, so yes, there

01:56:26.280 --> 01:56:33.360
[Guest]: is this family. There is a family, definitely. But you don't know their name. Only I know

01:56:33.360 --> 01:56:41.280
[Guest]: them. As long as I'm true to the family, in terms of the ways in which the family functions,

01:56:41.280 --> 01:56:47.640
[Guest]: the family dynamics, the family broader history, then I started making composite characters

01:56:47.640 --> 01:56:53.440
[Guest]: also. So there's some character that say, for instance, I would, you know, fit in from

01:56:53.440 --> 01:57:00.240
[Guest]: somewhere, put them in. That started, that was also a very intensely creative process.

01:57:00.240 --> 01:57:07.960
[Guest]: But also, then it was also diffused chances of easy identification. You know, people say,

01:57:07.960 --> 01:57:15.880
[Guest]: okay, but this is not like that in his family. And that's all done very deliberately. You

01:57:15.880 --> 01:57:21.560
[Guest]: know, some characters have been introduced. Because how does it matter to a reader that

01:57:21.560 --> 01:57:25.720
[Guest]: this family is actually there? Because you're not actually getting to know that the real

01:57:25.720 --> 01:57:31.520
[Guest]: family with that's the whole point of it you have, they have to be protected. They don't

01:57:31.520 --> 01:57:32.520
[Amit Varma]: want to be known.

01:57:32.520 --> 01:57:34.680
[Amit Varma]: How have they reacted to the book?

01:57:34.680 --> 01:57:42.120
[Guest]: They were very happy. There's the protagonist, she, she loved the cover. And she told me,

01:57:42.120 --> 01:57:51.200
[Guest]: she said, this is just like me. Well, you know, you're the artist, Oraljit Sen made

01:57:51.200 --> 01:57:55.280
[Guest]: the cover. And it's really a very beautiful cover. Very, very beautiful.

01:57:55.280 --> 01:58:02.280
[Guest]: So this is this is just like, you, you know, he's done such a good likeness of me. Well,

01:58:02.280 --> 01:58:12.880
[Guest]: he hadn't he had just this is his imagination. So yeah, but for obvious reasons, they don't

01:58:12.880 --> 01:58:19.160
[Guest]: want to keep the copy in their house. And that's a understandable and very, very sad.

01:58:19.160 --> 01:58:25.600
[Guest]: So it's very proud. And you know, she, and I know that there are times when she's very

01:58:25.600 --> 01:58:31.880
[Guest]: tempted to say, that's me. And I've told her, I said, you know, anytime you feel like saying

01:58:31.880 --> 01:58:37.840
[Guest]: so, it's your story, you say it. But then that's her call to make.

01:58:37.840 --> 01:58:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. So my, you know, my final question before I release you from the torment of this

01:58:43.000 --> 01:58:50.000
[Amit Varma]: non-airconditioned studio, is that, you know, the book is done. It might seem that it's

01:58:50.000 --> 01:58:54.480
[Amit Varma]: just a book of history, that the Tawaifs are a community, which is no more. But it seems

01:58:54.480 --> 01:59:00.700
[Amit Varma]: to me that especially in current times, it carries a lot of resonance, because this imposition

01:59:00.700 --> 01:59:05.840
[Amit Varma]: of morality, this imposition of a certain kind of narrative where some things are right

01:59:05.840 --> 01:59:10.040
[Amit Varma]: and some things aren't and where everything has to fit in. Some people belong, some don't.

01:59:10.040 --> 01:59:14.960
[Amit Varma]: Some people belong, some don't. And everything has to fit into these neat categories. Seems

01:59:14.960 --> 01:59:21.560
[Amit Varma]: to me now as oppressive for all of us, as you know, what happened to the Tawaifs was

01:59:21.560 --> 01:59:25.800
[Amit Varma]: oppressive for them. You know, so when you look at these current times, and you're also

01:59:25.800 --> 01:59:29.680
[Amit Varma]: someone who's a social activist yourself, you're active in all of this.

01:59:29.680 --> 01:59:32.720
[Guest]: That's a new role. I feel very strange when people say social activist.

01:59:32.720 --> 01:59:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Well, I mean, you started off the Not In My Name sort of...

01:59:35.840 --> 01:59:39.560
[Guest]: I think this dispensation has forced many of us to...

01:59:39.560 --> 01:59:40.560
[Amit Varma]: By default.

01:59:40.560 --> 01:59:45.720
[Guest]: By default, just forced us. Activism, I never thought, you know, that that is something

01:59:45.720 --> 01:59:50.480
[Guest]: I would be doing. But then they leave you with not much choice.

01:59:50.480 --> 01:59:54.440
[Amit Varma]: So I mean, I don't even know what my question is. It's kind of a lament. I'm like one of

01:59:54.440 --> 01:59:59.280
[Amit Varma]: those old men at those Q&As, who's, you know, not asking a question, but giving a comment.

01:59:59.280 --> 02:00:03.200
[Amit Varma]: But your book spoke to me also because of that reason. Because I think that what happened

02:00:03.200 --> 02:00:07.680
[Amit Varma]: to the Tawaifs, in a sense, is happening to all citizens who care about, you know, our

02:00:07.680 --> 02:00:13.800
[Amit Varma]: diversity and, you know, our sense of what India is. And is that something that also

02:00:13.800 --> 02:00:18.440
[Amit Varma]: kind of strikes you as, you know, someone who's made these films and written this book?

02:00:18.440 --> 02:00:25.880
[Guest]: Oh, it was very clear to me, while I was writing the book, because the latter part of the book,

02:00:25.880 --> 02:00:32.240
[Guest]: especially, was written and a lot of things changed in that period, in the life of my

02:00:32.240 --> 02:00:41.760
[Guest]: protagonist and so it's documented. And, and, and especially in the past five or six years,

02:00:41.760 --> 02:00:47.360
[Guest]: it was very obvious, you know, what was, you know, I could see it. I mean, I could see

02:00:47.360 --> 02:00:51.840
[Guest]: it, of course, at the level of, you know, what was happening around at a macro level

02:00:51.840 --> 02:01:02.400
[Guest]: and reacting, etc. But here I was dealing with a family and with my friend, who, you

02:01:02.400 --> 02:01:12.280
[Guest]: know, she's always, always been shamed, and, you know, victimized for identity. So fine,

02:01:12.280 --> 02:01:19.920
[Guest]: she was victimized for being a Tawaif. She left that far behind. It's leading, I want

02:01:19.920 --> 02:01:24.320
[Guest]: to reveal the book, but yeah, it's leading a certain life, which is very different. Book

02:01:24.320 --> 02:01:31.720
[Guest]: actually talks about it. It's, you know, very respectable life. How does she leave behind

02:01:31.720 --> 02:01:39.240
[Guest]: being Muslim? And now she's, she has to deal with being a Muslim in the India of today.

02:01:39.240 --> 02:01:46.360
[Guest]: And well, and also a single woman, you know, woman headed household with grandchildren,

02:01:46.360 --> 02:01:52.480
[Guest]: young grandchildren, it's a very vulnerable position to be in, especially in UP, to be

02:01:52.480 --> 02:01:59.320
[Guest]: in UP and in Banaras, to be a Muslim in Banaras. Although Banaras actually has a very sizable

02:01:59.320 --> 02:02:07.200
[Guest]: Muslim population, which is a very well kept secret. But it would strike me. And, you know,

02:02:07.200 --> 02:02:14.840
[Guest]: while I was writing the book, it really would come home to me because it was also the ongoing

02:02:14.840 --> 02:02:23.120
[Guest]: conversations. It was becoming more and more about her sense of identity as a Muslim then.

02:02:23.120 --> 02:02:30.680
[Guest]: And also this just completely, I mean, here is someone who I don't know of anyone, really

02:02:30.680 --> 02:02:40.760
[Guest]: I don't know of anyone who in her lived life and her practice, intensely a spiritual person,

02:02:40.760 --> 02:02:46.800
[Guest]: you know, there's a lot about Apa that I kind of go along with, but it's not that I fully

02:02:46.800 --> 02:02:54.640
[Guest]: understand because I'm not, I don't necessarily share that. But an intensely Catholic, you

02:02:54.640 --> 02:03:00.200
[Guest]: know, very Catholic in her belief systems completely. I mean, you know, the secularism,

02:03:00.200 --> 02:03:04.480
[Guest]: of course, means that you keep religion away from other aspects of life. But in the Indian

02:03:04.480 --> 02:03:09.600
[Guest]: context, secularism actually means when all religions are given that equal importance.

02:03:09.600 --> 02:03:16.040
[Guest]: She is the great one practitioner I know of that Indian version of secularism, you know,

02:03:16.040 --> 02:03:24.560
[Guest]: just genuinely, there's no bias, no prejudice, never. And I mean, come on, the person she

02:03:24.560 --> 02:03:31.480
[Guest]: had her longest relationship with, like her husband, her long standing love, was a Hindu.

02:03:31.480 --> 02:03:44.480
[Guest]: Her children had a Hindu come out of that union. So, I remember when, you know, in 2016-17,

02:03:44.480 --> 02:03:51.240
[Guest]: when the mob lynchings were at their peak, she's really perplexed. She just couldn't

02:03:51.240 --> 02:03:58.120
[Guest]: make sense of it. And she said, how can they do this? How do I explain to her, you know,

02:03:58.120 --> 02:04:03.840
[Guest]: this? And the point is that it's not happened overnight. The point is that there are, I

02:04:03.840 --> 02:04:11.280
[Guest]: think it's been, we might tend to now conveniently say, oh, 2014 was this, like, that's when

02:04:11.280 --> 02:04:16.880
[Guest]: things went bad. But I think the fact is, there's been a slide and there's for a very

02:04:16.880 --> 02:04:17.880
[Guest]: long time.

02:04:17.880 --> 02:04:22.160
[Guest]: I'd done an episode with Akshay Mukul on his book, The Gita Press, and this has been a

02:04:22.160 --> 02:04:24.760
[Guest]: strain in our society for decades.

02:04:24.760 --> 02:04:32.120
[Guest]: The Tawaf Nama, actually, people have commented. And I was conscious of it. I mean, it's not

02:04:32.120 --> 02:04:37.640
[Guest]: that I did it consciously. It's as much also a book about Hindu nationalism. And the fact

02:04:37.640 --> 02:04:44.440
[Guest]: that that dark underside of nationalism, which is Hindu nationalism, has always been present.

02:04:44.440 --> 02:04:52.360
[Guest]: It's just that, you know, it could, at certain ways, points, be balanced out. But it was

02:04:52.360 --> 02:04:54.480
[Guest]: always there.

02:04:54.480 --> 02:04:57.920
[Guest]: And almost as an extension of British colonialism.

02:04:57.920 --> 02:05:03.800
[Guest]: And then there's been a slide in, you know, I mean, especially from the 1980s onwards

02:05:03.800 --> 02:05:09.840
[Guest]: with the whole thing of opening up of Ram Mandir, you know, Ayodhya and all of that.

02:05:09.840 --> 02:05:18.000
[Guest]: I think that kind of, but it's not as if before that, it didn't exist. It was there. It was

02:05:18.000 --> 02:05:23.360
[Guest]: that darkness was there. You know, the so called non communal parties, they opened the

02:05:23.360 --> 02:05:28.920
[Guest]: doors for this, for them to come in and we are paying, all of us are paying the price

02:05:28.920 --> 02:05:29.920
[Guest]: for it today.

02:05:29.920 --> 02:05:36.080
[Guest]: And today, of course, I mean, the very existence, when she says she's panicked, she's paranoid,

02:05:36.080 --> 02:05:40.980
[Guest]: you know, this whole thing about not accessing courts and all. Now it doesn't hold because

02:05:40.980 --> 02:05:45.920
[Guest]: she is paranoid. She says, you know, about, she's been running around collecting every

02:05:45.920 --> 02:05:50.680
[Guest]: shred of paper about, you know, proving your identity.

02:05:50.680 --> 02:05:55.960
[Guest]: What do I say? You know, you boycott it. It's someone, she's one of the most vulnerable

02:05:55.960 --> 02:05:57.440
[Guest]: people.

02:05:57.440 --> 02:06:00.800
[Amit Varma]: And people like that can't afford to say hum kaagaz nahi dikhayenge, we can't afford to

02:06:00.800 --> 02:06:01.800
[Guest]: say that.

02:06:01.800 --> 02:06:06.480
[Guest]: The only way I believe in hum kaagaz nahi dikhayenge, but that has to be at a community

02:06:06.480 --> 02:06:12.600
[Guest]: level then. It cannot be at an individual level, because, you know, they just, the people

02:06:12.600 --> 02:06:19.160
[Guest]: are just so, so vulnerable. You can't push them into, you know, this and can't hold here

02:06:19.160 --> 02:06:20.720
[Guest]: in front of that.

02:06:20.720 --> 02:06:24.880
[Guest]: So I mean, if there has to be a, you know, this civil disobedience, well, then it has

02:06:24.880 --> 02:06:30.680
[Guest]: to be across localities or communities, whichever way it works best.

02:06:30.680 --> 02:06:39.040
[Guest]: So yeah, I mean, I have, strangely, you know, this book came out, and then from since last

02:06:39.040 --> 02:06:46.760
[Guest]: year and been busy with the thing of promoting it and going through the thing.

02:06:46.760 --> 02:06:54.400
[Guest]: And it's been fun, but it's also the danger that we are all in, and which is looming in

02:06:54.400 --> 02:07:01.840
[Guest]: a way, because we, well, we are inured by many things, you know, class and all of that.

02:07:01.840 --> 02:07:07.800
[Guest]: But the danger that India is in at the moment, I think that anyone, anyone with a modicum

02:07:07.800 --> 02:07:12.040
[Amit Varma]: of brains would see just, you know.

02:07:12.040 --> 02:07:16.040
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, that's what your very fine book is also about.

02:07:16.040 --> 02:07:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for coming on the show, Saba.

02:07:17.880 --> 02:07:18.880
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

